rg/facilities/camp-silver-fir/ Active]\n |\n|-\n | [[Camp Stephens]] ||[[Alameda Council]]||[[Pinecrest Lake]] || Closed || \n|-\n | [[Camp Tahquitz]] ||[[Long Beach Area Council]]||[[Angelus Oaks, California|Angelus Oaks]] ||[https://www.longbeachbsa.org/aboutus/tahquitz/ Active]|| \n|-\n | [[Camp Tamarancho]]|| Marin Council || Farifax ||[http://www.boyscouts-marin.org/camping-and-facilities/camp-tamarancho/4057 Active]\n|\n |-\n | [[Camp Three Falls]] || Ventura County Council || Frazier Park ||[https://www.vccbsa.org/Camping/Camp%20Three%20Falls/ Active]\n|\n|-\n|Camp Verdugo Oaks\n|Verdugo Hills Council\n|\n|[https://vhcbsa.org/facilities/camp-verdugo-oaks/ Active]\n|\n|-\n | [[Camp Whitsett]] ||[[Western Los Angeles County Council]]||  ||[http://www.campwhitsett.org/ Active]|| Located in the Sequoia National Forest.\n |-\n | [[Camp Winton]] ||[[Golden Empire Council]]||[[Bear River Reservoir]] || [http://www.gec-bsa.org/camping/campwinton Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Wolfeboro]] ||[[Mt Diablo Silverado Council]]||  ||[https://campwolfeboro.mdscbsa.org/ Active]|| located in Sierra Nevada Mountains near Angels Camp and Bear Valley. Started operating as a Boy Scout camp in 1928.\n |-\n | [[Camp Wolverton]] ||[[Western Los Angeles County Council]]||  || Closed || Located in the Sequoia National Park.\nClosed in 2012\n |-\n | [[Chesebrough Scout Reservation]] ||[[Silicon Valley Monterey Bay Council]]||  ||[http://svmbc.org/svmbc/campproperties/chesebrough-scout-reservation/ Active]|| Also called Camp Chesebrough, this is a 544-acre (2.2&nbsp;km\u00b2) Boy Scouts of America camp in the Santa Cruz Mountains of Santa Cruz and San Mateo counties, California.\n |-\n | [[Circle B Scout Ranch]] ||[[Old Baldy Area Council]]||  || Closed || Open from the late 1950s until 1974, it was located in the southern Sierra Nevada northeast of Lake Isabella and due west of China Lake Naval Weapons Station.\n |-\n | [[Camp Circle X|Circle X]] ||[[Los Angeles Area Council]]||[[Cedar Glen, California|Cedar Glen]]|| Active ||Camp Circle X at Big Horn.  Part of Hubert Eaton Scout Reservation.\n |-\n | [[Cutter Scout Reservation]] ||[[Pacific Skyline Council]]||[[Boulder Creek, California|Boulder Creek]] || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Firestone Scout Reservation]] ||[[Los Angeles Area Council]]||[[Brea, California|Brea]]  ||[https://www.glaacbsa.org/firestone Active]|| Located just east of State Route 57 in Tonner Canyon between Diamond Bar and Brea, California.\n |-\n | [[Forest Lawn Scout Reservation]]\naka Hubert Eaton Scout Reservation\n|[[Los Angeles Area Council]]||[[Lake Arrowhead, California|Lake Arrowhead]] ||[https://www.glaacbsa.org/Hubert_Eaton Active]|| Located 3 miles (5&nbsp;km) east of Lake Arrowhead, California, formerly known as the Lake Arrowhead Scout Camps. The Forest Lawn Scout Reservation consists of five active and one closed Boy and Cub Scout resident camps on more than 2,000 acres in the San Bernardino National Forest.  The six camps are:\n{|\n|-\n|\n* Circle X Ranch at Big Horn\n* Camp Pepperdine,\n* Camp Pitchess, formerly Camp Cedar (closed)\n|\n* Camp Pollock \u2013 adjacent to what was once Camp Pitchess\n* John Wayne Outpost \u2013 wilderness camping area\n* Northrop Family Camp\n|}\n |-\n | [[Glacial Trails Scout Ranch]] ||[[Golden Empire Council]]||[[Cisco Grove, California|Tahoe National Forest]] || Closed || Reopened as Camp Robert L. Cole.\n  |-\n | [[Holcomb Valley Scout Ranch]] ||[[San Gabriel Valley Council]]|| Big Bear ||[https://www.glaacbsa.org/holcomb Active]|| Located north of Big Bear Lake in the old mining district of Belleville in the Holcomb Valley, on the site of the old Hitchcock Ranch.\n |-\n | [[Holt Scout Ranch]] ||[[San Gabriel Valley Council]]||  || [http://www.lafavre.us/holt/Holt_Scout_Ranch.htm Closed] || Closed in 1974. Previously known as Camp Cedar Canyon\n |-\n | [[Irvine Ranch Outdoor Education Center]] ||[[Orange County Council]]||[[Orange, California|Orange]] ||[https://www.outdooreducationcenter.org/ Active]|| 190 Acres\n |-\n | [[Jubilee Scout Ranch]] ||[[Western Los Angeles County Council]]||  || Closed || Closed in 2003.\n |-\n | [[Log Cabin Wilderness Camp]] ||[[Los Angeles Area Council]]||[[Tioga Pass Road]] ||[https://www.glaacbsa.org/log_cabin Closed]|| Closed in 2016. \n |-\n | [[Long Beach Sea Base]] ||[[Long Beach Area Council]]||[[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] ||[https://www.longbeachbsa.org/aboutus/seabase/ Active]||\n |-\n | [[Lost Valley Scout Reservation]] ||[[Orange County Council]]||[[Warner Springs, California|Warner Springs]]||[https://www.ssrlv.org/ Active]|| Schoepe Scout Reservation at Lost Valley\n |-\n | [[Marina Wilderness Camp]] ||  ||  ||  ||\n |-\n | [[Mataguay Scout Reservation]] ||[[San Diego-Imperial Council]]\n|[[Santa Ysabel, California|Santa Ysabel]]\n|[https://camping.sdicbsa.org/MSR/ Active]\n|\n |-\n | [[Newport Sea Base]] ||[[Orange County Council]]||[[Newport Beach, California|Newport Beach]]||[https://www.newportseabase.org/ Active]||\n |-\n | [[Oso Lake]] ||[[Orange County Council]]||[[Rancho Santa Margarita, California|Rancho Santa Margarita]] ||[https://www.osolake.org/ Active]|| \n |-\n | [[Pardee Scout Sea Base]] ||[[Western Los Angeles County Council]]||[[Marina Del Rey, California|Marina Del Rey]] || Closed ||Closed in 2008\n|-\n | [[Pendola Sierra Adventure base]] ||[[Greater Yosemite Council]]||[[Emigrant Wilderness Area]] || [http://www.yosemitescouting.org/camping/pendola-sierra-adventure-base/51881 Active] ||\n|-\n | [[Rancho Alegre (California)|Rancho Alegre]] ||[[Los Padres Council]]||[[Lake Cachuma]] ||[https://www.lpcbsa.org/camping/ Active]||\n|-\n | [[Rancho Las Flores]] ||[[Orange County Council]]||  || Closed || At [[Camp Pendelton]]\n |-\n | [[Rancho Los Mochos]] ||[[Oakland Area Council (California)|Oakland Area Council]] / [[San Francisco Bay Area Council]]||[[Livermore, California|Livermore]]||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/RLM.html Active]  ||1945\u2013present.  Located in the hills south of Livermore.  640 acres. Three camping areas: Blue Oak Ridge, Manzanita Flats, and Deadwood.\n |-\n | [[Sierra North High Aadventure|Sierra North High Adventure]] ||  ||  ||  ||\n |-\n | [[Stockton Sea Scout Base]] ||  ||  ||  ||\n |-\n | [[Three Falls Camp]] ||[[Ventura County Council]]||  ||[https://www.vccbsa.org/camping/camp-three-falls/ Active]\n|\n |-\n | [[Trask Scout Reservation]] ||[[San Gabriel Valley Council]]||[[Monrovia, California|Monrovia]] ||[https://www.glaacbsa.org/trask Active]|| Located above the Sawpit Dam off of Monrovia Canyon Park.\n |-\n | [[Verdugo Pines]] ||  ||[[Valyermo, California|Valyermo]]\n| Closed ||Sold in 1963\n |-\n | [[Wente Scout Reservation / Willits Scout Reservation]] ||Oakland Area Council /  [[San Francisco Bay Area Council]]||[[Willits, California|Willits]]||[http://www.sfbac.org/camping/wentescoutreservation Active] ||1959\u2013present. 2200 acres located in the hills east of Willits.  First camping took place in October 1959, and the first summer camp took place in July 1964. It was renamed to Wente Scout Reservation in 1978 in honor of San Francisco Council Board Member and Bank of America President Carl F. Wente.\n |-\n | [[Will J. Reid Reservation]] ||[[Long Beach Area Council]]||[[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]]|| Closed ||Closed in 2010\n|}\n\n=== Colorado ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Colorado}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n | [[Ben Delatour Scout Ranch]] || Longs Peak Council ||[[Red Feather Lakes, Colorado]] || Active || Encompassing 3,200 acres at Red Feather Lakes, Colorado, it includes four Scout camps. \n{|\n|-\n|\n* Jack Nicol Cub Scout Camp\n* Camp Charles Jeffrey\n|\n* Camp Ruth Coffin\n* Elkhorn High Adventure Base\n|}\n |-\n | [[Camp Alexander]] || Pikes Peak Council || [[Eleven Mile Canyon]]  || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Laramie]] || Longs Peak Council ||[[Wheatland, Wyoming]] || Active || \n |-\n | [[Camp Patiya]] || Longs Peak Council ||[[Boulder, Colorado]] || Active || \n|-\n|[[Chimney Park Scout Camp]]  || Longs Peak Council ||[[Woods Landing, Wyoming]] || Active || \n |-\n | [[Tahosa High Adventure Base]] || Denver Area Council ||[[Ward, Colorado]] || Active || Located near Ward, Colorado this was the primary camp for the Denver area until the late 1970s, when it was shut down because of damage caused by environmental factors. The camp was recently re-opened as a high adventure base.\n  |-\n | [[O.A. Greager Scout Ranch]] || Western Colorado Council || [[Gypsum, Colorado]] || [http://www.troop97.net/col_camps.htm Closed] ||\n |-\n | [[Peaceful Valley Scout Ranch]] || Denver Area Council  ||[[Elbert, Colorado]] || Active || Built in the 1960s by the Army Corps of Engineers, the camp is located just outside Elbert, CO.\n |-\n | [[Rocky Mountain High Adventure Base]] ||[[Rocky Mountain Council]]||[[Poncha Springs, Colorado]] ||[https://rockymountainscouts.org/camp/rmhab/ Active]|| Formerly [[Packard High Adventure Base]].\n|-\n | [[San Isabel Scout Ranch]] ||[[Scouting in Colorado|Rocky Mountain Council]]||[[San Isabel, Colorado]]  || [http://www.SISRBSA.org Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Spanish Peaks Scout Ranch]] || Santa Fe Trail Council   || [[Walsenburg, Colorado]] || Active ||\n|}\n\n=== Connecticut ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Connecticut}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n | Camp Aquila (formerly Camp Mauwehu) || Connecticut Yankee Council ||[[Candlewood Lake]], [[Sherman, Connecticut|Sherman, CT]]||[http://www.ctyankee.org/fs/news/001773/powahaynews201205web.pdf Closed] || Located on Candlewood Lake in Sherman, CT., the camp was sold in 1982 along with Camp Toquam in Goshen.<ref name=\"Yankee Council\">{{cite web|title=Blast from the Past .... Fairfield County Council Camp Closings|url=http://www.ctyankee.org/fs/news/001773/powahaynews201205web.pdf|publisher=Connecticut Yankee Council: Powahay District|accessdate=28 May 2013|page=7|date=May 2012}}</ref> \n |-\n | [[Camp Cochipianee]] || Bristol Area Council || [[Goshen, Connecticut|Goshen, CT]] || Closed || The camp was founded in 1928 by the Bristol Area Council and was sold after the New Britain Area Council and the Bristol Area Council were merged in 1972.\n |-\n | [[Camp Irving]]  || Housatonic Council || [[Shelton, Connecticut|Shelton, CT]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20131021024930/http://www.housatonicbsa.org/Council/History/TrialsandTribulationsofStartingaScoutCamp.pdf Closed] || The camp was located in Shelton in the Birchbank area along the Housatonic River.  It was closed in 1945 and the buildings were razed in 1948.<ref>{{citation|last=Oscar|first=Johnson|title=The Trials and Tribulations of Starting a Scout Camp|page=3|url=http://www.housatonicbsa.org/Council/History/TrialsandTribulationsofStartingaScoutCamp.pdf|publisher=Housatonic Council|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021024930/http://www.housatonicbsa.org/Council/History/TrialsandTribulationsofStartingaScoutCamp.pdf|archivedate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n |-\n | [[Camp Mattatuck]] || Connecticut Rivers Council || [[Plymouth, Connecticut|Plymouth, CT]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150306003006/http://www.ctrivers.org/Camping/CampMattatuck Active] || [[Mattatuck Council]] purchased 170 acres in 1938 and the camp opened the following year. \n |-\n | [[Camp Nahaco]] || Connecticut Rivers Council || [[Woodstock, Connecticut|Woodstock, CT]]  ||  [http://www.daycampatcrystalpond.com/apps/blog/entries/show/12722538-did-you-know- Sold] || Previously called Camp Keemosabee, the camp was purchased by the towns of Woodstock and Eastford on March 3, 2003.  The 120 acre site is now permanently protected from development and the Boy Scouts still have use of the property.\n |-\n | Camp Pioneer || Long Rivers Council || [[New Hartford, Connecticut|New Hartford, CT]] || [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/doc/758738195.html Closed] || Located on the shores of West Hill Pond, adjacent to Camp Sequassen, it was sold in 1985 and has since been developed.\n |-\n | [[Camp Pomperaug]] || Connecticut Yankee Council || [[Union, Connecticut|Union, CT]]  || [http://www.ctyankee.org/camping/camps/camppomperaug Active] || For a time the camp was leased to the Ct Burn Foundation as a summer camp for children with severe burns; however, it has since been changed back into a Scout camp.\n |-\n | [[Camp Sequassen]] || Connecticut Yankee Council  || [[New Hartford, Connecticut|New Hartford, CT]] || [http://www.ctyankee.org/camping/camps/sequassen Active] || Located at 791 West Hill Road in New Hartford, Connecticut.\n |-\n | [[Camp Toquam]] || Connecticut Yankee Council || [[Goshen, Connecticut|Goshen, CT]] || [http://www.ctyankee.org/fs/news/001773/powahaynews201205web.pdf Closed] || The camp was sold in 1982 along with Camp Aquila in Sherman.<ref name=\"Yankee Council\" />\n |-\n | [[Camp Workcoeman]] || Connecticut Rivers Council ||[[New Hartford, Connecticut|New Hartford, CT]] || [http://campworkcoeman.org/ Active] || Established in 1924 and located on the shore of West Hill Pond.\n |-\n | [[Deer Lake Scout Reservation]] || Connecticut Yankee Council || [[Deer Lake (Connecticut)|Deer Lake]], [[Killingworth, Connecticut|Killingworth, CT]]||[http://www.ctyankee.org/camping/camps/deerlake Active] || It was originally owned by Central Connecticut Council until the merger with Quinnipiac Council. It is currently being upgraded to run the Connecticut Yankee Council's Cub Scout Summer Resident Camp.\n |-\n | [[Edmund D. Strang Scout Reservation]] || Housatonic Council ||[[Goshen, Connecticut|Goshen, CT]]  || [https://web.archive.org/web/20111107211956/http://www.housatonicbsa.org/campforms/camping_programs1.htm Active] || Formally called Housatonic Scout Reservation.\n |-\n | [[Ernest Thompson Seton Scout Reservation]] || Greenwich Council || [[Greenwich, Connecticut|Greenwich, CT]]  || Active || A 249-acre camp located off 363 Riversville Road in Greenwich. \n |-\n | [[Frederick Sprague Barbour Scout Reservation]] || Connecticut Rivers Council || [[Norfolk, Connecticut|Norfolk, CT]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150905224711/http://www.ctrivers.org/Camping/CampBarbour/ Active] || 106-acre wilderness camp\n|-\n | [[John Sherman Hoyt Scout Reservation]] || Connecticut Yankee Council || [[Redding, Connecticut|Redding, CT]] || [http://www.ctyankee.org/camping/camps/hoyt Active] || The 174 acre reservation was donated to the Alfred W. Dater Council by Alice B. Sanford in 1966.\n |-\n | [[June Norcross Webster Scout Reservation]] || Connecticut Rivers Council || [[Ashford, Connecticut|Ashford, CT]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130704110034/http://www.ctrivers.org/Camping/JuneNorcrossWebsterScoutReservation/ Active] || Originally opened as Camp Ashford on June 28, 1964, today the reservation occupies 1,200 acres (4.9 km2) of land.\n |-\n | [[Lake of Isles Scout Reservation]] || Long Rivers Council ||[[North Stonington, Connecticut|North Stonington, CT]] || Closed || This reservation included Camp Apache, Camp Pequot, and Camp Cherokee.  With the construction of the Mashantucket Pequot Casino in 1991\u20131992, the camp's surroundings had been changed enough that the Long Rivers Council decided to sell the property to the Native American tribe in 1992. The Mashantucket nation has since converted the land into a golf course.\n |-\n | [[Mark Greer Scout Reservation]] || Connecticut Rivers Council ||[[Bozrah, Connecticut|Bozrah, CT]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20131203003011/http://www.ctrivers.org/News/CampTadmaAnnouncement2013/ Sold] || It is home to Camp Tadma, a Cub Scout summer resident camp and Camp Wakenah, a Cub Scout day camp previously located on Gardner Lake in Salem. The reservation was known almost exclusively as Camp Tadma until 2004. Camp Tadma was closed in 2013, much to the sorrow of the staff and dedicated Scout troops who had grown to love the camp. The camp was sold in 2014 and is now owned by a church. \n |-\n | [[Wah Wah Tay See]] || Connecticut Yankee Council || [[North Haven, Connecticut|North Haven, CT]] || [http://www.ctyankee.org/camping/camps/wahwahtaysee Active] || \n|}\n\n=== Delaware ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Delaware}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n | [[Henson Scout Reservation]] || Del-Mar-Va Council || [[Galestown, Maryland]] || [http://www.doubleknot.com/OpenRosters/ViewOrgPageLink.aspx?orgkey=1516&linkkey=9338 Active] || Also known as [[Camp Nanticoke]], a 1,500-acre located on the Delmarva Peninsula.\n |-\n | [[Rodney Scout Reservation]] || Del-Mar-Va Council || [[North East, Maryland]] || [http://www.delmarvacouncil.org/rodney-scout-reservation/9340 Active] || The reservation includes Camp Lenape, Camp Pathfinder, and Camp Wilderness. It is located on 900 acres at the head of the Chesapeake Bay.\n |-\n | [[Akridge Scout Reservation]] || Del-Mar-Va Council || [[Dover, Delaware]] || [http://www.doubleknot.com/OpenRosters/ViewOrgPageLink.aspx?orgkey=1516&linkkey=35361 Active] || Located on {{convert|85|acre|km2|1}} of farmland in Dover, Delaware.\n|}\n\n=== Florida ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Florida}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\