ist|group=note}}\n{{Reflist}}\n<!-- footer -->\n{{Scouting}}\n{{Scoutorg BSA}}\n\n[[Category:Local council camps of the Boy Scouts of America|*]]\n[[Category:Scouting-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox WorldScouting\n|name=Local council camps of the Boy Scouts of America\n|image=File:Boy Scouts of America corporate trademark.svg\n|caption=Logo of the Boy Scouts of America\n}}\nThere are hundreds of '''local council camps of the Boy Scouts of America''' operated by the [[Boy Scouts of America]]. Some of these include:\n{{Horizontal TOC|nonum=y|limit=3}}\n\n== Within the 50 US states ==\n\n=== Alabama ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Alabama}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n  ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n | [[Camp Alaflo]]  || Alabama-Florida Council || [[Dothan, Alabama|Enterprise]]  || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130613213742/http://www.alflcouncilbsa.org/pages/campalaflo.html Active] || \n |-\n | [[Camp Arrowhead (Alabama)|Camp Arrowhead]] || Birmingham Area Council || [[Clanton, Alabama|Clanton]]  || [http://thisoldpatch.blogspot.com/2011/08/camp-arrowhead-1942-cherokee-fifty-1st.html Closed] || Camp Arrowhead operated from the early 1940s to 1971 and was located on the Coosa River.\n |-\n | [[Camp Horne]] || Black Warrior Council || [[Cottondale, Alabama|Cottondale]]  || [http://www.bwc-bsa.org/camping/camp-horne/27062 Active] || Located in east Tuscaloosa County, Camp Horne is a 496-acre facility.\n |-\n | [[Camp Jack Wright]] || Greater Alabama Council || [[McCalla, Alabama|McCalla]]  || [https://1bsa.org/camps.php Active] || Located in the Roupes Valley, adjacent to [[Tannehill Ironworks Historical State Park]].\n |-\n | [[Camp Jackson (Alabama)|Camp Jackson]] || Greater Alabama Council || [[Scottsboro, AL|Scottsboro]]  || [https://1bsa.org/camps.php Active] || Camp Jackson is a 515-acre primitive camp located 5 miles east of Scottsboro on the Tennessee River at Jones Cove.\n |-\n | [[Camp McKenzie]] || Birmingham Area Council || [[Pell City, Alabama|Pell City]]  || [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233423/http://winnataska.org/our-history/ Sold] || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://winnataska.org/heritage/|title=Camp Winnataska \u2013 Our Heritage|website=winnataska.org}}</ref>\n |-\n | [[Camp O'Rear]] || Black Warrior Council || [[Jasper, Alabama|Jasper]]  || [http://www.bwc-bsa.org/camping/camp-orear/27063 Active] || Camp O'Rear is a 90-acre primitive-style facility located in Jasper, AL.\n |-\n | [[Camp Pushmataha]] || Mobile Area Council || [[Citronelle, Alabama|Citronelle]]  || [https://web.archive.org/web/20120817171931/http://bsamac.org/camps_files/camps.htm Active] || Camp Pushmataha is no longer a council camp and is owned by the City of Citronelle. With a reservation from the city, Scout troops are welcome to camp there. It is a primitive camping facility. Pre-1960s it was the Mobile Area Council Camp.\n |-\n | [[Camp Westmoreland]] || Greater Alabama Council || [[Florence, Alabama|Florence]] || [https://1bsa.org/camp.php?cn=12 Closed] || First opened in the 1920s and closing in the 1980s, Camp Westmoreland is located in Lauderdale County.  However, it is still widely used to this day for both council and district activities. The camp was once a part of the Tennessee Valley Council, which merged with two other councils to form the Greater Alabama Council.\n |-\n | [[Camp Zinn]] || Choccolocco Council || [[Anniston, Alabama|Anniston]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130505131306/http://www.camplee.org/history_of_camp_lee.htm Sold] || Camp Zinn, in Dekalb County, operated from 1931 to 1965.  At a September 8, 1966 meeting, the Official Board of Camp Lee, a [[United Methodist Church]] organization, purchased the camp from the Choccolocco Council, and renamed it Camp Lee.\n |-\n | [[Frank Spain Scout Reservation]] || Greater Alabama Council || [[Delta, AL|Delta]] || [https://1bsa.org/camps.php Active] ||  Also called Camp Sequoyah, a 1,447 acre camp in east central Alabama, near [[Cheaha State Park]].\n |-\n | [[Hugh M. Comer Scout Reservation]] || Greater Alabama Council || [[Mentone, Alabama|Mentone]] || [https://1bsa.org/camp.php?cn=8 Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Maubila Scout Reservation]] || Mobile Area Council || [[Grove Hill, Alabama|Grove Hill]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20120817171931/http://bsamac.org/camps_files/camps.htm Active] || Camp Maubila is 680 acres.\n |-\n | [[Warner Scout Reservation]] || Tukabatchee Area Council || [[Prattville, Alabama|Prattville]] || [http://www.tukabatcheebsa.org/?pgID=camps Active] || Warner Scout Reservation includes two camps: [[Camp Tukabatchee]] and [[Camp Dexter C. Hobbs]].\n |-\n | [[White Bluff Scout Reservation]] || Black Warrior Council || [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]] || [http://www.bwc-bsa.org/camping/white-bluff-scout-reservation/27064 Active] || A primitive camp located north of Demopolis, Alabama.\n|}\n\n=== Alaska ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Alaska}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n | [[Camp Gorsuch]] || Great Alaska Council || [[Chugiak, Alaska|Mirror Lake]] || [http://www.scoutingalaska.org/index.php/camps/gorsuch Active]  || \n |-\n | [[Eagle River Scout Camp]] || Great Alaska Council || [[Juneau]] ||  [https://scoutingevent.com/segroup.php?OrgKey=BSA610&ag=7 Active]  ||\n |-\n | [[Denali High Adventure Scout Base]] || Great Alaska Council || [[Fairbanks North Star Borough, Alaska|Fairbanks North Star Borough]] ||  [http://www.scoutingalaska.org/index.php/98-mnm/camps/144-denali-high-advanture-base Active]  ||\n |-\n | [[Lost Lake Scout Camp]]  || Midnight Sun Council || [[Salcha, Alaska|Salcha]] || [https://archive.today/20130616112905/http://www.midnightsunbsa.org/lost_lake.html Active]  || 400 acres, located 58.5 miles south of Fairbanks.\n|}\n\n=== Arizona ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Arizona}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp Name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n | [[Camp Geronimo]] || Grand Canyon Council || [[Payson, Arizona|Payson]] || Active<ref name=\"gcbsa\"/> ||  Located between Payson, Arizona and Pine, Arizona, near the [[Mogollon Rim]]. Camp Geronimo incorporates the former [[Spade Ranch (Arizona)|Spade Ranch house]].\n |-\n | [[Camp Lawton (BSA)|Camp Lawton]] || Catalina Council  || [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]]  || Active<ref name =\"catalina\">{{cite web | url = http://www.catalinacouncil.org/outdoorprograms/council-camps/camp-lawton-2 | title = Camp Lawton}} </ref> || Located on land, leased from the US forest service since 1921, in the Santa Catalina mountains outside of Tucson, Arizona.\n |-\n | [[Camp Levi Levi]] || Las Vegas Area Council || [[Kingman, AZ|Kingman]]  || <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lvacbsa.org/summer-camp/camp-levi-levi/8488  | title =  Camp Levi Levi}}</ref> || Located in the Hualapai Mountains 14 miles south of Kingman, Arizona, at an elevation of 7,000 feet.\n |-\n | [[Double V Scout Ranch]] || Catalina Council  || [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]]  || Active<ref name = \"catalina2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.catalinacouncil.org/outdoorprograms/council-camps/double-v-scout-ranch | title = Double V Scout Ranch}}</ref>|| Located on 360-acre six miles southwest of Tucson, near Tucson Mountain Park's Cat Mountain. The ranch was acquired on a long-term lease from the Bureau of Land Management in 1969.\n |-\n | [[Heard Scout Pueblo]] || Grand Canyon Council || [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]  || Active<ref name=\"gcbsa\"/> || Located near 20th Street and Baseline Road in Phoenix, Arizona.\n |-\n | [[Lake Pleasant Camp]] || Grand Canyon Council || [[Peoria, Arizona|Peoria]] || Active<ref name=\"gcbsa\"/> || An aquatics and nature based camp located at the Desert Outdoor Center at Lake Pleasant 20 miles north of central Phoenix in Peoria, Arizona. It is operated in cooperation with the Maricopa County Parks Department \n |-\n | [[R-C Scout Ranch]] || Grand Canyon Council || [[Payson, Arizona|Payson]]  || Active<ref name=\"gcbsa\"/>  | title =</ref> || Located a half-hour east of Payson, the ranch is available to Boy Scout troops and Cub Scout packs for camping.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://r-crocks.com | title = R-C Scout Ranch}}</ref>\n |-\n | [[Raymond Scout Reservation]] || Grand Canyon Council || [[Parks, Arizona|Parks]] || Active<ref name=\"gcbsa\">{{cite web | url = http://www.grandcanyonbsa.org/outdoor-programs/council-camps/5824 | title= GC BSA Outdoor Programs}}</ref> || Located 30 miles outside of Flagstaff, Arizona, between the Kaibab National Forest and the Coconino National Forest, along the rim of Sycamore Canyon.\n |}\n\n=== Arkansas ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Arkansas}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n  ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n | [[Camp Cedar Valley]] || Eastern Arkansas Council  || [[Hardy, Arkansas|Hardy]] || [http://www.eaac.org/camp/ccv.htm Sold]  || This camp served the Eastern Arkansas Council from 1942 to 1966, when it was sold to a developer.  It was located 5.5 miles southwest of Hardy, AR on the Spring River.  Originally 95 acres, an additional land purchase brought this up to 255 acres.\n |-\n | [[Camp De Soto]] || De Soto Area Council || [[El Dorado, Arkansas|El Dorado]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130905113833/http://desotoareacouncil.org/id10.html Active] || Located outside Junction City, AR.\n |-\n | [[Camp Orr]] || Westark Area Council || [[Harrison, Arkansas|Harrison]] || [http://www.westarkbsa.org/Camping/CampOrr/ Active] || Camp Orr has been in use since 1955 and covers nearly 600 acres of the Buffalo National River Wilderness Area.  It is the only Boy Scout camp situated within a National Park.<ref>{{cite web|title=Camp Orr|url=http://www.westarkbsa.org/Camping/CampOrr/ |publisher=Westark Area Council|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> \n |-\n | [[Pine Trail Reservation/Camp Cedar Valley]] || Eastern Arkansas Council  || [[Viola, Arkansas|Viola]] || [http://www.eaac.org/camp/ccv.htm Sold]  || In 2002, after the merger of the Eastern Arkansas Area Council into the Quapaw Area Council, Camp Cedar Valley was promptly sold to a private owner. It is still an active camp, on 777 acres just south of Viola, Arkansas on U.S. 412, in the foothills of the Ozark Mountains.\n |-\n | [[Camp Pioneer (Arkansas)|Camp Pioneer]] || Caddo Area Council || [[Hatfield, Arkansas|Hatfield]] || [http://www.camppioneer.org Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Preston Hunt]] || Caddo Area Council ||[[Texarkana, Arkansas|Texarkana]]  || [http://www.caddobsa.org/index.php?fuseaction=services.category&Category_ID=39&PHPSESSID=a6c9a1b20b54f5cfdf1a652293a73d6b Active] || \n  |-\n | [[Camp Quapaw]] || Quapaw Area Council || [[Benton, Arkansas|Benton]]  || [http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=3754 Closed] || Camp Quapaw opened in 1925 and was located on the Saline River west of Benton in Saline County. In 1976 when Camp Kiwanis was purchased, Camp Quapaw was then closed and  the land was later sold.\n |-\n | [[Camp Spencer]] || Westark Area Council || [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]] || [http://www.westarkbsa.org/Camping/CampOrr/ Active]  || A 100-acre primitive camping facility, located on the shore of Lake Norfork, east of Mountain Home, AR.\n |-\n | [[Gus Blass Scout Reservation]] || Quapaw Area Council ||[[Damascus, Arkansas|Damascus]]  || [http://www.camprockefeller.org/ Active]  || Purchased in 1976, the reservation includes Camp Rockefeller and the Donald W. Reynolds Scout Training Center, located west of Damascus, Arkansas.  The reservation was named the Cove Creek Scout Reservation and Camp Nile Montgomery until 2001.\n |-\n | [[Kia Kima Scout Reservation]] || Chickasaw Council || [[Hardy, Arkansas|Hardy]] || [http://www.kiakima.com Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Rhodes Scout Reservation]] || Ouachita Area Council ||[[Bismarck, Arkansas|Bismarck]] || [http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=3754 Sold] || In 2012, after the merger of Ouachita Area Council and the Quapaw Area Council, the Rhodes Scout Reservation, a 16,000+ acre camp on Lake DeGray in Bismarck, AR, was sold to the Ouachita Camp Foundation, in partnership with the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the Ross Foundation.  It is still available for use by the troops of the Quapaw Area Council as a private campsite.\n |-\n | [[Rogers Scout Reservation]] ||  Westark Area Council || [[Booneville, Arkansas|Booneville]] || [http://www.westarkbsa.org/Camping/RogersScoutReservation/ Active]  || In 1973 the Arkansas State Legislature permitted the Westark Area Council to purchase 2,842 acres of the [[Booneville, Arkansas#State Tuberculosis Sanatorium|Booneville Sanatorium]], just south of Booneville, Arkansas, which is now known as the Rogers Scout Reservation.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Westark Area Council History|journal=Wachtschu Mawachpo Lodge|date=January 7, 2012|page=15|url=http://www.westarkbsa.org/files/d/usr/317/2012_Lodge_559_Rules-History_74-85_Aug7-08_Updated_11-20-2010.pdf}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== California ===\n{{Details|Scouting in California}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"