p was located on Washington Lake. It was sold in the early 1980s.\n |-\n | [[Camp Kiroliex]] || [[Chief Okemos Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council) || [[Waterloo Township, Michigan|Waterloo Township]] || Closed || The camp was located on Clear Lake in Waterloo Township, Michigan.\n |-\n | [[Camp Kiwanis]] || Saginaw Kiwanis Club || [[Mason, Michigan|Mason]] || [http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampKiwanis/ Closed] || 85 acres located 3.5 miles east of Mason, Michigan on M-36 at Diamond Road. \n |-\n | [[Camp Madron]] || [[Southwest Michigan Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council)|| [[Buchanan, Michigan|Buchanan]]  || Sold || Was located on Madron Lake and sold in 1985. \n |-\n | [[Camp Mills]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Munhacke]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Gregory, Michigan|Gregory]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130122053239/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampMunhacke/ Active] || Michigan Crossroads council announced in October, 2019, the camp will be closed in January, 2020.\n |-\n | [[Camp Neyati]] || [[Summer Trails/Paul Bunyan Council]] || [[Lake, Clare County, Michigan|Lake, Michigan]]  ||  Closed  ||  Closed in 1962, and is now owned and operated by Midland Community Foundation.\n |-\n | [[Camp Northwinds]] || [[Southwest Michigan Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council)|| [[Eden Township, Mason County, Michigan|Eden Township]]  || Sold || 1,280 camp located in Mason County. Sold in 1991.\n |-\n | [[Camp Pine Lake]] || [[Tall Pine Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council) || [[Linden, Michigan|Linden]] || Closed ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Rotary]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Clare, Michigan|Clare]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130712174655/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampRotary Active] || The campground is owned by the Saginaw Rotary Club, but leased by the Boy Scouts.  Camp Rotary offers 1,180 acres of year around camping just north of Clare, MI, on old US-27.\n |-\n | [[Camp Shawondasee]] || || [[Whitehall, Michigan|Whitehall]] || Closed || Originally located near West Olive (Port Sheldon) on Lake Michigan (1916\u20131927) it re-located to  Duck Lake, near Whitehall, Michigan, in 1927 the property was acquired by the Nature Conservancy in the early 1970s and is now part of Duck Lake State Park. Gerald R. Ford was a camp staff member there in 1927\u201328.\n|-\n| [[Camp Silver Lake]] || Detroit Area Council ||  || Sold ||\n |-\n | [[Camp T. Ben Johnston]] || [[Southwest Michigan Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council)|| [[Augusta, Michigan|Augusta]]  || Sold || Closed in the 1980s and reverted to the W. K. Kellogg Foundation. It now operates as Sherman Lake YMCA camp.\n |-\n | [[Camp Tapico]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Kalkaska, Michigan|Kalkaska]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20141020031658/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampTapico/ closed] || Camp Tapico is located in the eastern region of Kalkaska County just north of M-72 between Grayling and Traverse City. Sold and closed.\n |-\n | [[Camp Teetonkah]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Jackson, Michigan|Jackson]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130122053250/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampTeetonkah/ Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Wabaningo]] || Evanston North Shore Area Council ([[Northeast Illinois Council]]) || [[Whitehall, Michigan|Whitehall]] || Sold || Closed and sold after the Evanston Council and Northshore Area Council merged in 1969.\n |-\n | [[Camp Weidman]] || Water and Woods Field Service Council || || Active || Located four miles west of Mt. Pleasant, just off M-20. \n |-\n | Camp Wilderness ||  || [[Bridgman, Michigan|Bridgman]] || Sold || Land was purchased by Rotary Club of Oak Park\u2013River Forest (IL) and donated to their local Scout council in the 1920s.  In 1945 it was sold to the State of Michigan and became part of [[Warren Dunes State Park]].<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2010-04-14 |title=Scouting, Rotary have long history in Oak Park |url=https://www.clubrunner.ca/Data/6450/4371/html/88140/RAZZ_APR_14_2010.pdf |magazine=The Rotary Razz |location= |publisher=Rotary Club of Oak Park \u2013 River Forest, IL |access-date=2020-02-10 }}</ref>\n |-\n | [[Charles Howell Scout Reservation]] || Detroit Area Council (Michigan Crossroads Council) || [[Brighton, Michigan|Brighton]] || Sold || Located on Brighton Lake. Sold in 1986.\n |-\n | [[Cole Canoe Base]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Moffatt Township, Michigan|Alger]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130524151041/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/ColeCanoeBase/ Active] ||\n |-\n | [[D-Bar-A Scout Ranch]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Metamora, Michigan|Metamora]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130530071706/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/D-AScoutRanch/ Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Gerber Scout Reservation]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Twin Lake, Michigan|Twin Lake]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130716060028/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/GerberScoutReservation Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Lost Lake Scout Reservation]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Garfield Township, Clare County, Michigan|Lake]] || [http://www.michiganscouting.org/pubs/MCC_Strategic_Plan_for_Camp_Properties_2014_2024.pdf Closed]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} || Closed in 2012.\n |-\n | [[Northwoods Scout Reservation]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Lupton, Michigan|Lupton]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130122053311/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/NorthwoodsScoutReservation/ closed] || 840 acres located near West Branch in Ogemaw County, Michigan. \n |-\n | [[Owasippe Scout Reservation]] || Chicago Area Council (Now Pathway to Adventure Council) || [[Twin Lake, Michigan|Twin Lake]] || [http://www.chicagobsa.org/camping/owasippe-scout-reservation/3820 Active] ||  4,800 acres located near Twin Lake, Michigan. Oldest Boy Scout Camp in continuous operation. Since 1911. \n