xt-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|19.7% ''291''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''65.2%''' ''963''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|15.1% ''223''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1916 United States presidential election|1916]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|5.5% ''50''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''94.6%''' ''868''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1912 United States presidential election|1912]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|2.5% ''26''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''57.8%''' ''600''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|39.8% ''413''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Morris N. Abrams]], educator <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lahistory.org/site18.php|title=Abrams, Morris Newton|publisher=[[Louisiana Hoistorical Association]], A Dictionary of Louisiana Biography  (lahistory.org)|accessdate=December 24, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101110024226/http://www.lahistory.org/site18.php|archivedate=November 10, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Oscar K. Allen|O.K. Allen]], [[governor of Louisiana]]\n* [[Bryant W. Bailey]], [[politician]], Winn Parish sheriff from 1908 to 1912\n* [[William Edenborn]], inventor and industrialist<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/19826616|first= Eric J. | last= Brock |title=William Edenborn|work= Find A Grave Memorial |publisher=www.findagrave.com |accessdate=2010-08-23 }}</ref>\n* [[T. H. Harris]], Louisiana state superintendent of education from 1908-1940\n* [[Huey Long]], governor of Louisiana\n* [[Earl Kemp Long]], governor of Louisiana\n* [[Charlton Lyons]], [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate for governor in 1964, practiced law in Winnfield prior to 1930\n* [[Keith M. Pyburn]], state representative for Caddo Parish from 1948 to 1952; born and resided in Dodson in Winn Parish from 1910 to 1925\n* [[Terry Reeves]], district attorney for Winn Parish from 1991 until his death in office in 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/11789525|title=Terry Ray Reeves|author=Ron Manley|publisher=findagrave.com|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Terry Reeves|Calvin Marion Robinson]], sheriff of Winn Parish prior to 1956\n* [[Roy Sanders (Louisiana politician)|Roy Sanders]], educator and state representative from [[Natchitoches Parish]] from 1948 to 1952; born in Winn Parish\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Winn Parish, Louisiana]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Winn Parish, Louisiana\n|North     = [[Jackson Parish, Louisiana|Jackson Parish]]\n|Northeast = [[Caldwell Parish, Louisiana|Caldwell Parish]]\n|East      =\n|Southeast = [[La Salle Parish, Louisiana|La Salle Parish]]\n|South     = [[Grant Parish, Louisiana|Grant Parish]]\n|Southwest =\n|West      = [[Natchitoches Parish, Louisiana|Natchitoches Parish]]\n|Northwest = [[Bienville Parish, Louisiana|Bienville Parish]]\n}}\n\n{{Winn Parish, Louisiana}}\n{{Louisiana parishes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Coord|31.95|-92.64|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-LA_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n[[Category:Louisiana parishes]]\n[[Category:Winn Parish, Louisiana|*]]\n[[Category:1852 establishments in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1852]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county          = Winn Parish\n| state           = Louisiana\n| type            = [[Louisiana parishes|Parish]]\n| official_name   = Parish of Winn\n| founded year    = 1852\n| founded date    = February 24\n| seat wl         = Winnfield\n| largest city wl = Winnfield\n| area_total_sq_mi = 957\n| area_land_sq_mi = 950\n| area_water_sq_mi = 6.7\n| area percentage = 0.7\n| population_as_of = 2010\n| population_total = 15313\n| pop_est_as_of    = 2018\n| population_est   = 14134\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| time zone       = Central\n| footnotes       =\n| web             =\n| ex image = Winn Parish, LA, Courthouse MVI_2727.jpg\n| ex image size = 250px\n| ex image cap = Winn Parish Courthouse in Winnfield\n| named for       = [[Walter Winn]] or [[Winfield Scott]]\n| district = 5th\n}}\n\n[[Image:Winn Parish Enterprise building MVI 2718.jpg|200px|right|thumb|''[[Winn Parish Enterprise]]'' newspaper office in Winnfield]]\n\n[[Image:Evergreen Missionary Baptist Church in Winn Parish, LA IMG 1881.JPG|thumb|right|200px|The Evergreen Missionary Baptist Church and Cemetery, with a green roof and large bell, is located off [[U.S. Highway 71]] in northwestern Winn Parish south of [[Saline Bayou]]. Country churches of this kind are common in North Louisiana.]]\n\n[[Image:Saline Bayou (Winn-Natchitoches Parish, LA) IMG 7496 1.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Saline Bayou]]\n\n[[Image:2015 backwater flooding in Winn Parish, LA MG_7194.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Backwater flooding in Winn Parish led temporarily in June 2015 to a detour around [[U.S. Highway 71]] at [[St. Maurice, Louisiana|St. Maurice]], Louisiana.]]\n\n'''Winn Parish''' is a [[List of parishes in Louisiana|parish]] located in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Louisiana]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the population was 15,313.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/22/22127.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=August 18, 2013}}</ref> Its [[parish seat|seat]] is [[Winnfield, Louisiana|Winnfield]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> The parish was founded in 1852.<ref name=CCET>{{cite web|url=http://ccet.louisiana.edu/tourism/parishes/North_Louisiana/winn.html|title=Winn Parish|publisher=Center for Cultural and Eco-Tourism|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref> It is last in alphabetical order of Louisiana's sixty-four parishes.\n\nWinn is separated from [[Natchitoches Parish, Louisiana|Natchitoches Parish]] along [[U.S. Highway 71]] by [[Saline Bayou]], the first [[Blackwater river|blackwater]] protected waterway in the [[American South]].\n\n==History==\nWinn Parish was established in 1852 from lands which had belonged to the parishes of [[Catahoula Parish, Louisiana|Catahoula]], [[Natchitoches Parish, Louisiana|Natchitoches]], and [[Rapides Parish, Louisiana|Rapides]].<ref name=CCET/>\n\nDuring the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], David Pierson, a young attorney, was elected to represent the parish at the Secession Convention called in January 1861 in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]] by [[Governor of Louisiana|Governor]] [[Thomas Overton Moore]]. Pierson voted against secession and refused, along with several others, to change his \"no\" vote at the end of the process when asked to do so to make the final tally unanimous.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\nThere was little military action in Winn Parish during the Civil War, but there was a problem with [[conscript]]s fleeing into the wooded areas to avoid military duty{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}. The [[Confederate States Army]] defeated a Union detachment sent to destroy a salt works in the parish. Winn Parish contributed to the $80,000 raised to build fortifications on the nearby [[Red River of the South|Red River]].<ref>[[John D. Winters]], ''The Civil War in Louisiana'', Baton Rouge: Louisiana State University Press, 1963, {{ISBN|0-8071-0834-0}}, pp. 164, 310</ref>\n\nAfter the war, bandits roamed the [[Natchez Trace]] or [[Harrisonburg Road]] that ran through the lower part of the parish. Among the worst were the West and Kimbrell clan. For seven years they preyed especially on travelers and migrants passing through the area.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G_mSCwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA49&ots=K4I4bxpmta&dq=natchez%20trace%20west%20kimbrell%20clans&pg=PA48#v=onepage&q=natchez%20trace%20west%20kimbrell%20clans&f=false|title=Legendary Louisiana Outlaws: The Villains and Heroes of Folk Justice|last=LeJeune|first=Keagan|publisher=LSU Press|year=2016|isbn=9780807162590|location=Baton Rouge|pages=48\u201349|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1873, white Democrats forming a militia from Winn Parish joined with ex-Confederate veterans from Rapides and Grant parishes against Republican blacks in the [[Colfax Massacre]] in neighboring [[Grant Parish, Louisiana|Grant Parish]].<ref>Keith, Leeanna, ''The Colfax Massacre: The Untold Story of Black Power, White Terror, & The Death of Reconstruction,'' New York: Oxford University Press, 2007</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Lane |first=Charles |authorlink=Charles Lane (journalist) |title=The Day Freedom Died: The Colfax Massacre, the Supreme Court, and the Betrayal of Reconstruction |location=New York |publisher=Henry Holt & Company |year=2008 |url=https://archive.org/details/dayfreedomdiedco00lane |url-access=registration |ref=harv}}</ref> They attacked [[freedmen]] defending the parish courthouse and two Republican officeholders in the aftermath to the disputed gubernatorial election of 1872. Among the 80-150 blacks killed were at least 50 who had surrendered; a total of three white men were killed in the confrontation.\n\nWinn Parish is the home of the former Long family Democratic political dynasty, started by [[Huey Long]]. It is the birthplace of three [[Governor#United States|governor]]s of Louisiana.  Governor Earl Long is buried in Winnfield in a public square known as the Earl K. Long State Park.\n\nSince 1956, Winn Parish has had three sheriffs named \"Jordan.\" R. Sanford Jordan, a Democrat, served from 1956 to 1976.<ref name=jordan>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepineywoods.com/JordanJan12.htm|title=Tom Kelly, \"Third Sheriff Jordan elected in Winn Parish,\" 2011|publisher=thepineywoods.com|accessdate=March 4, 2012}}</ref> A second but unrelated Jordan, James Edward \"Buddy\" Jordan (1942-2012),<ref>Buddy Jordan obituary, ''[[The Town Talk (Alexandria)|Alexandria Daily Town Talk]]'', February 23, 2012</ref> was the sheriff from 1992 to 2008, when he was defeated by a 10-vote margin by a fellow Democrat, Albert D. \"Bodie\" Little.<ref>Louisiana Secretary of State, General election returns, November 17, 2007</ref> Subsequently,  A. D. Little was forced from office in 2011 and convicted thereafter on federal drug charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov/usao/law/news/wdla20120224.pdf|title=\"Former Sheriff of Winn Parish Found Guilty:  Federal Jury Convicts A. D. \"Bodie\" Little of Drug Charges Tonight,\" February 24, 2012|publisher=justice.gov|accessdate=March 4, 2012}}</ref>\nCranford Jordan, Jr. (born 1952), a nephew of Sanford Jordan, won the office on his third attempt in the November 2011 general election and took office in July 2012. Cranford Jordan is an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]].<ref name=jordan/>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the parish has a total area of {{convert|957|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|950|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|6.7|sqmi}} (0.7%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_22.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=September 2, 2014|date=August 22, 2012|title=2010 Census Gazetteer Files|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928155956/http://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_22.txt|archivedate=September 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Major highways===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Image:US 71.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Highway 71]]\n*[[Image:US 84.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Highway 84]]\n*[[Image:US 167.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Highway 167]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 34.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 34]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 126.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 126]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 127.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 127]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 156.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 156]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 471.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 471]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 499.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 499]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 500.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 500]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 501.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 501]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 505.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 505]]\n*[[Image:Louisiana 1228.svg|20px]] [[Louisiana Highway 1228]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Adjacent parishes===\n*[[Jackson Parish, Louisiana|Jackson Parish]] (north)\n*[[Caldwell Parish, Louisiana|Caldwell Parish]] (northeast)\n*[[La Salle Parish, Louisiana|La Salle Parish]] (southeast)\n*[[Grant Parish, Louisiana|Grant Parish]] (south)\n*[[Natchitoches Parish, Louisiana|Natchitoches Parish]] (west)\n*[[Bienville Parish, Louisiana|Bienville Parish]] (northwest)\n\n===National protected area===\n*[[Kisatchie National Forest]] (part)\n*[[Saline Bayou]]\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1860= 6876\n|1870= 4954\n|1880= 5846\n|1890= 7082\n|1900= 9648\n|1910= 18357\n|1920= 16119\n|1930= 14766\n|1940= 16923\n|1950= 16119\n|1960= 16034\n|1970= 16369\n|1980= 17253\n|1990= 16269\n|2000= 16894\n|2010= 15313\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=14134\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2016.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=October 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=September 2, 2014}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=September 2, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/la190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=September 2, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=September 2, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"QF\"/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 16,894 people, 5,930 households, and 4,234 families residing in the parish.  The [[population density]] was 18 people per square mile (7/km\u00b2).  There were 7,502 housing units at an average density of 8 per square&nbsp;mile (3/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the parish was 66.27% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 32.03% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.50% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.16% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.05% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.13% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.86% from two or more races.  0.87% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race. 35.9% were of [[United States|American]], 7.2% [[Irish people|Irish]] and 4.9% [[English American|English]]  ancestry according to [[Census 2000]].\n\nThere were 5,930 households out of which 32.60% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.80% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 15.30% had a female householder with no husband present, and 28.60% were non-families. 26.20% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.90% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.55 and the average family size was 3.07.\n\nIn the parish the population was spread out with 24.80% under the age of 18, 9.60% from 18 to 24, 28.90% from 25 to 44, 22.70% from 45 to 64, and 14.00% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females there were 110.80 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 113.20 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the parish was $25,462, and the median income for a family was $31,513. Males had a median income of $29,094 versus $17,939 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the parish was $11,794.  About 17.00% of families and 21.50% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 28.40% of those under age 18 and 24.20% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Education==\n[[Winn Parish School Board]] operates local public schools.\n\nThere is also the Huey P. Long Campus of [[Louisiana Technical College]] in Winnfield. The facility is being relocated from downtown to north of Winnfield on [[U.S. Highway 167]]. Funding for the structure was obtained by former [[Louisiana State Legislature|State Senator]] [[Mike Smith (Louisiana politician)|Mike Smith]] of Winnfield.\n\n==New Winn Parish Library==\nA new Winn Parish Library opened in Winnfield in 2014. The 11,000 square-foot building cost $2.5 million and houses 75,000 books, 420 periodicals, and sixteen computer stations. There are also facilities for children, special-needs citizens, genealogy and history buffs, and access to on-line higher-education studies.<ref name=newlibrary>Tom Kelly, \"New library open in Winnfield\", ''The Piney Woods Journal'', November 2014, pp. 1, 2</ref>\n\nPublic libraries in Louisiana began as early as 1920, with the establishment of the Louisiana Library Commission, the forerunner to the State Library of Louisiana. Assistance from the [[Carnegie library|Carnegie Foundation]] began in 1925. The Winn Parish facility opened in 1937 during the administration of [[governor of Louisiana|Governor]] [[Richard Leche]] in a former bank building on Main Street. Winn was the first of three parishes to vote a library tax millage. In 1940, property owners voted for a three-mil maintenance tax for the library. After [[World War II]], the library was moved to a wooden building, also on Main Street and one block west of the parish courthouse. In 1954, a brick structure replaced the wooden building at the same location, a project pushed by the then library director, Ruby Hanks. After sixty years, the new library now sits at the corner of Main and St. John streets. Construction of the facility was financed by a $2 million [[bond issue]] approved by voters in 2012. It is maintained by a now eight=mil property tax.<ref name=newlibrary/>\n\nThere are also branch libraries in Atlanta, Calvin, Dodson, and Sikes, with a total collection in the branches of nearly 80,000 books.<ref name=newlibrary/>\n\n==Corrections==\n[[Corrections Corporation of America]], under contract with [[Louisiana Department of Public Safety and Corrections]], operates the [[Winn Correctional Center]] in an unincorporated section of Winn Parish.<ref>\"[http://www.doc.louisiana.gov/view.php?cat=7&id=49 Winn Corr. Center] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915111642/http://www.doc.louisiana.gov/view.php?cat=7&id=49 |date=2008-09-15 }}.\" ''[[Louisiana Department of Public Safety and Corrections]]''. Accessed September 14, 2008.</ref>\n\n==National Guard==\nA Company 199TH FSB (Forward Support Battalion) previously resided in [[Winnfield, Louisiana]].  This unit deployed twice to [[Iraq]] as part of the [[256th Infantry Brigade Combat Team (United States)|256TH IBCT]] in 2004-5 and 2010. \u00a0The unit\u2018s Winnfield Armory was closed.\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Map of Winn Parish Louisiana With Municipal and District Labels.PNG|thumb|right|Map of Winn Parish, with municipal labels and districts]]\n\n=== City ===\n* [[Winnfield, Louisiana|Winnfield]] (parish seat and largest municipality)\n\n=== Town ===\n* [[Tullos, Louisiana|Tullos]] (partial)\n\n===Villages===\n*[[Atlanta, Louisiana|Atlanta]]\n*[[Calvin, Louisiana|Calvin]]\n*[[Dodson, Louisiana|Dodson]]\n*[[Sikes, Louisiana|Sikes]]\n\n=== Census-designated places ===\n* [[Jordan Hill, Louisiana|Jordan Hill]]\n* [[Joyce, Louisiana|Joyce]]\n* [[Saint Maurice, Louisiana|Saint Maurice]]\n\n=== Unincorporated communities===\n* Packton<ref>{{gnis|547810|Packton}}</ref>\n* [[Tannehill, Louisiana|Tannehill]]\n\n==Hospital==\n* [[Winn Parish Medical Center]]\n\n==Politics==\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential elections results'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|last=Leip|first=David|website=uselectionatlas.org|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third parties]]\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2016 United States presidential election|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''72.3%''' ''4,608''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|25.8% ''1,644''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.9% ''120''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2012 United States presidential election|2012]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''69.5%''' ''4,541''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|29.4% ''1,919''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.1% ''74''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2008 United States presidential election|2008]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''68.4%''' ''4,632''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|30.2% ''2,047''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.4% ''93''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2004 United States presidential election|2004]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''67.1%''' ''4,366''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|31.6% ''2,056''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.3% ''85''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2000 United States presidential election|2000]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''63.3%''' ''4,028''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|34.1% ''2,167''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.6% ''166''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1996 United States presidential election|1996]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|37.6% ''2,803''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''50.6%''' ''3,779''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|11.8% ''881''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1992 United States presidential election|1992]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|38.8% ''2,932''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''46.9%''' ''3,537''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|14.3% ''1,080''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1988 United States presidential election|1988]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''59.0%''' ''4,165''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|38.3% ''2,699''\n|  style=\"t