can}}|'''78.5%''' ''4,366''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|21.5% ''1,193''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1960 United States presidential election|1960]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''44.9%''' ''1,839''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|27.1% ''1,108''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|28.1% ''1,149''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1956 United States presidential election|1956]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''49.6%''' ''1,736''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|35.0% ''1,225''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|15.5% ''542''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1952 United States presidential election|1952]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|46.5% ''1,915''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''53.5%''' ''2,206''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Dixiecrat}}|'''[[1948 United States presidential election|1948]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|11.4% ''333''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|32.1% ''940''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|'''56.6%''' ''1,657''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1944 United States presidential election|1944]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|38.6% ''881''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''61.4%''' ''1,403''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1940 United States presidential election|1940]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|13.0% ''382''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''87.0%''' ''2,552''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1936 United States presidential election|1936]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|9.6% ''254''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''90.4%''' ''2,393''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1932 United States presidential election|1932]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|1.6% ''36''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''96.7%''' ''2,172''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.7% ''38''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1928 United States presidential election|1928]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|31.5% ''533''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''68.5%''' ''1,161''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1924 United States presidential election|1924]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|13.1% ''120''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''86.9%''' ''797''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1920 United States presidential election|1920]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|19.7% ''291''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''65.2%''' ''963''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|15.1% ''223''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1916 United States presidential election|1916]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|5.5% ''50''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''94.6%''' ''868''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1912 United States presidential election|1912]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|2.5% ''26''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''57.8%''' ''600''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|39.8% ''413''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Morris N. Abrams]], educator <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lahistory.org/site18.php|title=Abrams, Morris Newton|publisher=[[Louisiana Hoistorical Association]], A Dictionary of Louisiana Biography  (lahistory.org)|accessdate=December 24, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101110024226/http://www.lahistory.org/site18.php|archivedate=November 10, 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Oscar K. Allen|O.K. Allen]], [[governor of Louisiana]]\n*[[Bryant W. Bailey]], [[politician]], Winn Parish sheriff from 1908 to 1912\n* [[William Edenborn]], inventor and industrialist<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/19826616|first= Eric J. | last= Brock |title=William Edenborn|work= Find A Grave Memorial |publisher=www.findagrave.com |accessdate=2010-08-23 }}</ref>\n*[[T. H. Harris]], Louisiana state superintendent of education from 1908-1940\n*[[Huey Long]], governor of Louisiana\n*[[Earl Kemp Long]], governor of Louisiana\n*[[Charlton Lyons]], [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate for governor in 1964, practiced law in Winnfield prior to 1930\n*[[Keith M. Pyburn]], state representative for Caddo Parish from 1948 to 1952; born and resided in Dodson in Winn Parish from 1910 to 1925 \n* [[Terry Reeves]], district attorney for Winn Parish from 1991 until his death in office in 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/11789525|title=Terry Ray Reeves|author=Ron Manley|publisher=findagrave.com|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> \n*[[Terry Reeves|Calvin Marion Robinson]], sheriff of Winn Parish prior to 1956\n*[[Roy Sanders (Louisiana politician)|Roy Sanders]], educator and state representative from [[Natchitoches Parish]] from 1948 to 1952; born in Winn Parish\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Winn Parish, Louisiana]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Winn Parish, Louisiana\n|North     = [[Jackson Parish, Louisiana|Jackson Parish]]\n|Northeast = [[Caldwell Parish, Louisiana|Caldwell Parish]]\n|East      =\n|Southeast = [[La Salle Parish, Louisiana|La Salle Parish]]\n|South     = [[Grant Parish, Louisiana|Grant Parish]]\n|Southwest =\n|West      = [[Natchitoches Parish, Louisiana|Natchitoches Parish]]\n|Northwest = [[Bienville Parish, Louisiana|Bienville Parish]]\n}}\n\n{{Winn Parish, Louisiana}}\n{{Louisiana parishes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Coord|31.95|-92.64|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-LA_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n[[Category:Louisiana parishes]]\n[[Category:Winn Parish, Louisiana|*]]\n[[Category:1852 establishments in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1852]]\n", "name_user": "Whoisjohngalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Winn_Parish,_Louisiana"}
{"title_page": "NUKEMAP", "text_new": "'''NUKEMAP''' is an interactive map using [[Mapbox]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wellerstein/status/1055172046882328584|title=To give numbers: to handle the 200K map loads per month that NUKEMAP gets, Google wants to charge me >$1000 a month. Even if I ran ads, that's not sustainable. It's crazy. Fortunately MapBox makes for a perfect alternative (esp. w/LeafLet), and has totally reasonable rates. (2/3)|first=Alex|last=Wellerstein|date=October 24, 2018}}</ref> [[Application programming interface|API]] and declassified [[nuclear weapon]]s effects data, created by [[Alex Wellerstein]], a historian of science at the [[Stevens Institute of Technology]] who studies the history of nuclear weapons. The initial version was created in February 2012, with major upgrades in July 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.nuclearsecrecy.com/2013/07/25/the-nukemaps-are-here/ |title=The NUKEMAPs are here &#124; Restricted Data |website=Blog.nuclearsecrecy.com |date=2013-07-25 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref><ref name=wmdjunction>{{cite web |last=Wellerstein |first=Alex |url=http://wmdjunction.com/120503_nukemap_educational_tool.htm |title=So Long, Mom, I'm Off to Drop the Bomb: A Case Study in Public Usage of an Educational Tool |website=wmdjunction.com |date=2012-05-04 |accessdate=2013-08-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727144044/http://wmdjunction.com/120503_nukemap_educational_tool.htm |archive-date=2013-07-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.nuclearsecrecy.com/ |title=Restricted Data: The Nuclear Secrecy Blog |website=Blog.nuclearsecrecy.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> which enables users to model the explosion of [[nuclear weapon]]s (contemporary, historical, or of any given arbitrary yield) on virtually any terrain and at virtually any altitude of their choice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/nuke-map-explosion-2013-7 |title=This Scary Interactive Map Shows What Happens If A Nuke Explodes In Your Neighborhood |website= [[Business Insider]] |first= Brian |last= Jones |date=2013-07-16 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> A variation of the script, NUKEMAP3D, featured rough models of [[mushroom cloud]]s in 3D, scaled to their appropriate sizes.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/07/23/nukemap-3d-simulation-_n_3638461.html |title=NukeMap 3D: Google Earth Sim Lets You Model Nuclear Strikes On Any Location |website=[[Huffingtonpost|Huffington Post UK]] |date=2013-07-23 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.slashdot.org/story/13/07/21/1736217/interactive-nukemap-now-in-3d |title=Interactive Nukemap Now In 3D - Slashdot |website=[[Slashdot]] |date= 2013-07-21|accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> NUKEMAP3D is no longer functional as Google deprecated the Google Earth plugin.\n\nThe computer simulation of the effects of nuclear detonations has been described both as \"stomach-churning\" (by Wellerstein himself) and as \"the most fun I\u2019ve had with Google Maps since\u2026 well, possibly ever\" despite the admittedly abjectly grim nature of the subject.<ref>{{cite news|author=Drew Bowling |url=http://www.webpronews.com/nukemap-uses-google-maps-api-to-let-you-blow-up-the-outside-world-2012-02 |title=NUKEMAP Uses Google Maps API To Let You Blow Up The Outside World |website=WebProNews |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> Originally intended in part as a pedagogical device to illustrate the stark difference in scale between [[nuclear fission|fission]] and [[nuclear fusion|fusion]] bombs, more than three million people as of 2012 have exploded some 30 million virtual nuclear warheads;<ref>{{cite web|last=Terdiman |first=Daniel |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13772_3-57383763-52/nukemap-shall-we-play-a-game/ |title=Nukemap: Shall we play a game? &#124; Geek Gestalt - CNET News |website=[[CNET#News|CNET News]] |date=2012-02-23 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> having gone [[viral phenomenon|viral]], the increased popularity of the website necessitated a move to new servers.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost1\"/> The website averages five \"nukes\" per visitor.<ref name=wmdjunction/> According to the site's own counter, in November 2016 users had simulated over 90 million nuclear explosions. Wellerstein's Nukemap has garnered some popularity amongst [[nuclear strategy|nuclear strategists]] as an open source tool for calculating the costs of nuclear exchanges.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r45HDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA42|title=The Logic of American Nuclear Strategy: Why Strategic Superiority Matters|last=Kroenig|first=Matthew|date=2018|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190849191|location=New York City|page=42|author-link=Matthew Kroenig}}</ref> As of November 2019, more than 184 million nukes have been \"dropped\" on the site.\n\nThe NUKEMAP was a finalist for the [[National Science Foundation]]'s Visualization Challenge in 2071.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevens.edu/news/content/nuclear-weapons-data-visualization-reaches-finals-national-science-foundation%E2%80%99s-vizzies |title=Nuclear Weapons Data Visualization Reaches Finals of National Science Foundation\u2019s \"Vizzies\" Award |date= 2014-11-11 | publisher=Stevens Institute of Technology |accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|War|Nuclear Technology}}\n* [[Computer simulation]]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.nuclearsecrecy.com/nukemap/}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Nuclear weapons]]\n[[Category:Scientific simulation software]]\n", "text_old": "'''NUKEMAP''' is an interactive map using [[Mapbox]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wellerstein/status/1055172046882328584|title=To give numbers: to handle the 200K map loads per month that NUKEMAP gets, Google wants to charge me >$1000 a month. Even if I ran ads, that's not sustainable. It's crazy. Fortunately MapBox makes for a perfect alternative (esp. w/LeafLet), and has totally reasonable rates. (2/3)|first=Alex|last=Wellerstein|date=October 24, 2018}}</ref> [[Application programming interface|API]] and declassified [[nuclear weapon]]s effects data, created by [[Alex Wellerstein]], a historian of science at the [[Stevens Institute of Technology]] who studies the history of nuclear weapons. The initial version was created in February 2012, with major upgrades in July 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.nuclearsecrecy.com/2013/07/25/the-nukemaps-are-here/ |title=The NUKEMAPs are here &#124; Restricted Data |website=Blog.nuclearsecrecy.com |date=2013-07-25 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref><ref name=wmdjunction>{{cite web |last=Wellerstein |first=Alex |url=http://wmdjunction.com/120503_nukemap_educational_tool.htm |title=So Long, Mom, I'm Off to Drop the Bomb: A Case Study in Public Usage of an Educational Tool |website=wmdjunction.com |date=2012-05-04 |accessdate=2013-08-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727144044/http://wmdjunction.com/120503_nukemap_educational_tool.htm |archive-date=2013-07-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.nuclearsecrecy.com/ |title=Restricted Data: The Nuclear Secrecy Blog |website=Blog.nuclearsecrecy.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> which enables users to model the explosion of [[nuclear weapon]]s (contemporary, historical, or of any given arbitrary yield) on virtually any terrain and at virtually any altitude of their choice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/nuke-map-explosion-2013-7 |title=This Scary Interactive Map Shows What Happens If A Nuke Explodes In Your Neighborhood |website= [[Business Insider]] |first= Brian |last= Jones |date=2013-07-16 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> A variation of the script, NUKEMAP3D, featured rough models of [[mushroom cloud]]s in 3D, scaled to their appropriate sizes.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/07/23/nukemap-3d-simulation-_n_3638461.html |title=NukeMap 3D: Google Earth Sim Lets You Model Nuclear Strikes On Any Location |website=[[Huffingtonpost|Huffington Post UK]] |date=2013-07-23 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.slashdot.org/story/13/07/21/1736217/interactive-nukemap-now-in-3d |title=Interactive Nukemap Now In 3D - Slashdot |website=[[Slashdot]] |date= 2013-07-21|accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> NUKEMAP3D is no longer functional as Google deprecated the Google Earth plugin.\n\nThe computer simulation of the effects of nuclear detonations has been described both as \"stomach-churning\" (by Wellerstein himself) and as \"the most fun I\u2019ve had with Google Maps since\u2026 well, possibly ever\" despite the admittedly abjectly grim nature of the subject.<ref>{{cite news|author=Drew Bowling |url=http://www.webpronews.com/nukemap-uses-google-maps-api-to-let-you-blow-up-the-outside-world-2012-02 |title=NUKEMAP Uses Google Maps API To Let You Blow Up The Outside World |website=WebProNews |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> Originally intended in part as a pedagogical device to illustrate the stark difference in scale between [[nuclear fission|fission]] and [[nuclear fusion|fusion]] bombs, more than three million people as of 2012 have exploded some 30 million virtual nuclear warheads;<ref>{{cite web|last=Terdiman |first=Daniel |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13772_3-57383763-52/nukemap-shall-we-play-a-game/ |title=Nukemap: Shall we play a game? &#124; Geek Gestalt - CNET News |website=[[CNET#News|CNET News]] |date=2012-02-23 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> having gone [[viral phenomenon|viral]], the increased popularity of the website necessitated a move to new servers.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost1\"/> The website averages five \"nukes\" per visitor.<ref name=wmdjunction/> According to the site's own counter, in November 2016 users had simulated over 90 million nuclear explosions. Wellerstein's Nukemap has garnered some popularity amongst [[nuclear strategy|nuclear strategists]] as an open source tool for calculating the costs of nuclear exchanges.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r45HDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA42|title=The Logic of American Nuclear Strategy: Why Strategic Superiority Matters|last=Kroenig|first=Matthew|date=2018|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190849191|location=New York City|page=42|author-link=Matthew Kroenig}}</ref> As of November 2019, more than 184 million nukes have been \"dropped\" on the site.\n\nThe NUKEMAP was a finalist for the [[National Science Foundation]]'s Visualization Challenge in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevens.edu/news/content/nuclear-weapons-data-visualization-reaches-finals-national-science-foundation%E2%80%99s-vizzies |title=Nuclear Weapons Data Visualization Reaches Finals of National Science Foundation\u2019s \"Vizzies\" Award |date= 2014-11-11 | publisher=Stevens Institute of Technology |accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|War|Nuclear Technology}}\n* [[Computer simulation]]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.nuclearsecrecy.com/nukemap/}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Nuclear weapons]]\n[[Category:Scientific simulation software]]\n", "name_user": "98.1.39.160", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NUKEMAP"}
{"title_page": "Tropical Storm Danielle (1992)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=Tropical Storm Danielle\n| Type=Tropical storm\n| Year=1992\n| Basin=Atl\n| Image location=Danielle 25 sept 1992 1916Z.jpg\n| Image name=Tropical Storm Danielle off the coast of North Carolina on September 25\n| Formed=September 22, 1992\n| Dissipated=September 26, 1992\n| 1-min winds=55\n| Pressure=1001\n| Damages=\n| Fatalities=2 direct\n| Areas=[[North Carolina]], [[Virginia]], [[Maryland]], [[Delaware]], [[New Jersey]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| Hurricane season=[[1992 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n}}\n'''Tropical Storm Danielle''' was a strong tropical storm that made landfall on [[Virginia]] in the [[1992 Atlantic hurricane season]]. The fourth storm of the season, Danielle was one of two tropical cyclones in the year to make landfall in the [[United States]], the other being [[Hurricane Andrew]]. It formed out of a stationary trough of low pressure on September 18 near the coast of [[North Carolina]]. The system quickly reached tropical storm status, and Danielle looped to the west due to a change in steering currents. Tropical Storm Danielle reached a peak of 65&nbsp;mph (105&nbsp;km/h) winds before weakening and hitting the [[Delmarva Peninsula]]. The storm quickly dissipated over land.\n\nThe storm dropped light rainfall throughout its path, and winds were minimal. The combination of Danielle and a high pressure system produced higher than normal tides and strong waves, causing beach erosion and light coastal damage. The waves killed two in New Jersey from a boat sinking, and also destroyed three houses in the [[Outer Banks]] of North Carolina. Overall damage from the storm was minimal.\n\n== Meteorological history ==\n{{storm path|Danielle 1992 track.png}}\nA surface trough of low pressure with an area of convection persisted off the southeast coast of the [[United States]] on September 18. On the same day, a weak tropical wave which moved off the coast of [[Africa]] on September 8 approached the area. A cold front merged with the stationary area of disturbed weather on September 20, and on September 22 a circulation developed 200&nbsp;miles (325&nbsp;km) southeast of [[Cape Hatteras]], [[North Carolina]].<ref name=\"nhcreportpg1\">{{cite web|author=Miles Lawrence|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report Page One|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/prenhc/prelim01.gif}}</ref> Organization continued as outflow became better defined, and the system developed into Tropical Depression Six later that day.<ref name=\"disc1\">{{cite web|author=Lixion Avila|year=1992|title=Tropical Depression Six Discussion One|publisher=NHC|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/tropdisc/nal0792.001}}</ref>\n\nThe depression rapidly organized and attained tropical storm status with winds of 50&nbsp;mph (80&nbsp;km/h) just six hours after forming, upon which it was named [[Danielle]]. In response to an approaching trough, Danielle initially moved to the northeast. However, the trough outran the system, and a developing high pressure system to its north resulted in Danielle executing a tight, anticyclonic loop on September 23 to the 24th. The storm strengthened as it turned to the northwest, and reached a peak of 65&nbsp;mph (105&nbsp;km/h) winds on September 25 while just off the northeastern coast of North Carolina. Danielle turned to the north-northwest, and made landfall on the [[Eastern Shore of Virginia|Eastern Shore]] of [[Virginia]] late on the 25th. It rapidly weakened over land, and dissipated over eastern [[Pennsylvania]] on September 26.<ref name=\"nhcreportpg1\"/>\n\n== Preparations ==\n[[File:Danielle radar.JPG|right|thumb|Radar image of Danielle making landfall on September 25]]\nEarly in its life, forecasters had difficulties regarding the future track and intensity of Danielle, including a northeastward motion instead of its loop. After Danielle executed its loop, forecasters consistently predicted a landfall along the northeastern [[North Carolina]] coastline.<ref name=\"nhcreportpg2\">{{Cite report|author=Miles B. Lawrence|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report|page=2|publisher=NHC|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/prenhc/prelim02.gif}}</ref> As a result, officials issued [[Tropical cyclone warnings and watches|Tropical Storm Warnings]] for the coast of North Carolina on September 24, 36&nbsp;hours before the storm passed to the east of the state. The continued northward motion caught forecasters off guard, and consequentially tropical storm warnings were not issued for the [[Delmarva Peninsula]] until just 12&nbsp;hours before the storm made landfall. In addition, forecasters issued tropical storm warnings from [[Delaware]] through [[Watch Hill, Rhode Island]], as a precaution.<ref name=\"nhcreportpg5\">{{cite web|author=Miles B. Lawrence|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report|page=5|publisher=NHC|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/prenhc/prelim05.gif}}</ref>\n\nIn [[North Carolina]], ferry operations between [[Ocracoke, North Carolina|Ocracoke]] and the mainland at [[Hyde County, North Carolina|Hyde County]] were closed, while officials canceled schools in [[Dare County, North Carolina]] due to the approaching storm.<ref name=\"kdcnews\">{{Cite web|author=Virginia Pilot|year=1992|title=Danielle destroys three beach cottages|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/news/vp0926p2.gif}}</ref> Several families voluntarily evacuated St. George's Island in southern [[St. Mary's County, Maryland]].<ref name=\"bwipr\">{{cite web|author=Davis|year=1992|title=Danielle Preliminary Report|publisher=Baltimore National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/pshbwi.gif}}</ref> In addition, officials in [[Delaware]] recommended evacuations for low-level areas and beaches. As a precaution, officials set up two shelters in [[Kent County, Delaware|Kent County]].<ref name=\"ilg5\">{{cite web|author=James N. Roets|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Summary for Delaware|publisher=Wilmington National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/ilg05.gif}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n\n=== North Carolina ===\nThe pressure gradient between Tropical Storm Danielle and a ridge of high pressure to its north produced moderately strong winds across eastern [[North Carolina]], peaking at 58&nbsp;mph (93&nbsp;km/h) at [[Alligator River National Wildlife Refuge|Alligator River Bridge]]. Several other locations reported over tropical storm force winds. The pressure gradient also produced higher than normal waves along the coastline, with a maximum of 20&nbsp;feet (6&nbsp;m) at [[Duck, North Carolina|Duck]].<ref name=\"rdu03\">{{cite web|author=Glenn A. Field|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Report|publisher=Raleigh National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-05|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/rdu03.gif}}</ref> Despite passing close to the coastline, Danielle dropped only light rainfall, totaling to 0.2&nbsp;inches (5&nbsp;mm) at [[Cape Hatteras, North Carolina|Cape Hatteras]].<ref name=\"hatpsh\">{{cite web|author=Demaurice|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report|publisher=Cape Hatteras National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-05|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/pshhat.gif}}</ref> However, locations in the central portion of the state experienced over 1&nbsp;inch (25&nbsp;mm) of rainfall.<ref name=\"rain\">{{cite web|author=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|year=2005|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Rainfall Summary|accessdate=2006-08-05|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/danielle1992.html}}</ref>\n\nWaves and high tides from the storm caused flooding along the [[Pamlico Sound]] side of [[Ocracoke, North Carolina|Ocracoke]] and southern [[Hatteras Island]]. High tides also resulted in overwash in [[Pea Island]], forcing the closure of [[North Carolina Highway 12|Highway 12]] due to 12&nbsp;inches (305&nbsp;mm) of salt water. High tides from the storm also destroyed two houses in [[South Nags Head, North Carolina|South Nags Head]] and one in [[Rodanthe, North Carolina|Rodanthe]], two of which were previously condemned after the [[1991 Perfect Storm]]. Three other houses in the Outer Banks were threatened by the storm.<ref name=\"hatpsh\"/> Elsewhere in the Outer Banks, damage was minimal, and was limited to pedestrian ramps and steps to the beachfront.<ref name=\"kdcnews\"/>\n\n=== Mid-Atlantic ===\n\nIn [[Virginia]], Tropical Storm Danielle produced peak wind gusts of 61&nbsp;mph (98&nbsp;km/h) at [[Cape Henry]], though sustained winds remained below tropical storm strength. Rainfall was light along the coast, totaling to around 0.34&nbsp;inches (8.6&nbsp;mm).<ref name=\"norfnws\">{{cite web|author=Norfolk National Weather Service|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report|accessdate=2006-08-06|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/pshorf.gif}}</ref> However, outer bands of the storm produced heavier rainfall in the center portion of the state, peaking at 4.09&nbsp;inches (103.88&nbsp;m) at [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]].<ref name=\"metsum\">{{cite report|author=Miles B. Lawrence|year=1992|title=Meteorological Statistics for Danielle|publisher=NHC|accessdate=2006-08-06|page=4|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/prenhc/prelim04.gif}}</ref> The storm also produced higher than usual tides, peaking at 4.42&nbsp;feet (1.3&nbsp;m) at the mouth of the [[Elizabeth River (Virginia)|Elizabeth River]] in [[Sewell's Point|Sewells Point]],<ref name=\"norfnws\"/> as well as strong waves along the Virginia coastline. The waves caused significant overwash, leaving parts of [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]] under 2&nbsp;feet (.6&nbsp;m) of water. Several homes, businesses, and cars were flooded, as well. The waves also eroded beaches along the coast.<ref name=\"vapilot\">{{cite web|author=Steve Stone|year=1992|title=Coast is spared the worst of unpredictable Danielle|publisher=Virginia Pilot|accessdate=2006-08-06|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/news/vp0926p1.gif}}</ref> Overall, damage was minimal, and there were no reports of deaths or injuries.<ref name=\"norfnws\"/>\n\nUpon making landfall Danielle produced an estimated storm tide of 2 to 3&nbsp;feet (.6 to .9&nbsp;m) in [[Ocean City, Maryland|Ocean City]], [[Maryland]]. Wind gusts peaked at 53&nbsp;mph (85&nbsp;km/h), also in Ocean City.<ref name=\"bwipr\"/> The storm produced moderate rainfall of over 3&nbsp;inches (76&nbsp;mm) across the [[Eastern Shore of Maryland]],<ref name=\"rain\"/> while interior amounts experienced slightly lesser amounts of up to 2.79&nbsp;inches (71&nbsp;mm) in [[Pasadena, Maryland|Pasadena]]. Waves from the storm caused minor to moderate beach erosion along the coastline, and the combination of waves and high tides caused moderate street flooding. Near [[Salisbury, Maryland|Salisbury]], the storm produced a possible hook echo, though no tornadoes were reported. Danielle caused no deaths or injuries in the state.<ref name=\"bwipr\"/>\n\nIn [[Delaware]], the storm dropped light precipitation, with a maximum amount of 3.75&nbsp;inches (95&nbsp;mm) in [[Smyrna, Delaware|Smyrna]]. Wind gusts peaked at 66&nbsp;mph (106&nbsp;km/h) at [[Cape Henlopen]].<ref name=\"metsum\"/> Danielle caused 2 to 3-foot (.6 to .9-m) higher than normal tides, along with strong waves. The combination of the two flooded some coastal houses<ref name=\"ilg5\"/> and resulted in significant beach and dune erosion. The waves also sank four boats and washed away a dock near [[Slaughter Beach, Delaware|Slaughter Beach]].<ref name=\"ilg1\">{{cite web|author=James N. Roets|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Summary for Delaware|publisher=Wilmington National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-08|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/ilg01.gif}}</ref> Gusty winds caused power outages in [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]], while persistent rainfall caused sewer interruptions. Overall, with the exception of the severe beach erosion, damage was minimal.<ref name=\"ilg6\">{{cite web|author=James N. Roets|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Summary for Delaware|publisher=Wilmington National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-08|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/ilg06.gif}}</ref>\n\n=== Northeast United States ===\nTropical Storm Danielle dropped light rainfall across much of [[New Jersey]], with some areas in the southwestern portion of the state experiencing over 3&nbsp;inches (76&nbsp;mm).<ref name=\"rain\"/> Strong waves from the storm washed out miles of beaches along the coastline. In [[Ocean City, New Jersey|Ocean City]], the waves passed over the boardwalk and into houses. Further north, the waves crashed a four-person, 35-foot (10-m) sailboat near [[Island Beach State Park]]. Two managed to swim safely to shore,<ref name=\"mhdan\">{{cite web|author=Associated Press|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm blamed on one death|accessdate=2006-08-09|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/news/mh0927p1.gif}}</ref> though the other two occupants drowned.<ref name=\"nccanes\">{{Cite web|author=James E. Hudgins|year=2000|title=Tropical cyclones affecting North Carolina since 1586|publisher=National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-09|url=http://repository.wrclib.noaa.gov/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1002&context=nws_tech_memos|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070311045226/http://repository.wrclib.noaa.gov/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1002&context=nws_tech_memos |archivedate = March 11, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDanielle's outer bands dropped light rainfall from [[Connecticut]] through [[Maine]], with isolated locations in [[Rhode Island]] and [[Massachusetts]] reporting over 3&nbsp;inches (76&nbsp;mm). Damage in New England is unknown.<ref name=\"rain\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n* [[Hurricane Danielle (disambiguation)|Other storms of the same name]]\n* [[List of North Carolina hurricanes]]\n* [[List of New Jersey hurricanes]]\n* [[Timeline of the 1992 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Tropical Storm Danielle (1992)}}\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{1992 Atlantic hurricane season buttons}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Danielle (1992)}}\n[[Category:1992 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Atlantic tropical storms]]\n[[Category:1992 natural disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=Tropical Storm Danielle\n| Type=Tropical storm\n| Year=1992\n| Basin=Atl\n| Image location=Danielle 25 sept 1992 1916Z.jpg\n| Image name=Tropical Storm Danielle off the coast of North Carolina on September 25\n| Formed=September 22, 1992\n| Dissipated=September 26, 1992\n| 1-min winds=55\n| Pressure=1001\n| Damages=\n| Fatalities=2 direct\n| Areas=[[North Carolina]], [[Virginia]], [[Maryland]], [[Delaware]], [[New Jersey]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| Hurricane season=[[1992 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n}}\n'''Tropical Storm Danielle''' was a strong tropical storm that made landfall on [[Virginia]] in the [[1992 Atlantic hurricane season]]. The fourth storm of the season, Danielle was one of two tropical cyclones in the year to make landfall in the [[United States]], the other being [[Hurricane Andrew]]. It formed out of a stationary trough of low pressure on September 18 near the coast of [[North Carolina]]. The system quickly reached tropical storm status, and Danielle looped to the west due to a change in steering currents. Tropical Storm Danielle reached a peak of 65&nbsp;mph (105&nbsp;km/h) winds before weakening and hitting the [[Delmarva Peninsula]]. The storm quickly dissipated over land.\n\nThe storm dropped light rainfall throughout its path, and winds were minimal. The combination of Danielle and a high pressure system produced higher than normal tides and strong waves, causing beach erosion and light coastal damage. The waves killed two in New Jersey from a boat sinking, and also destroyed three houses in the [[Outer Banks]] of North Carolina. Overall damage from the storm was minimal.\n\n== Meteorological history ==\n{{storm path|Danielle 1992 track.png}}\nA surface trough of low pressure with an area of convection persisted off the southeast coast of the [[United States]] on September 18. On the same day, a weak tropical wave which moved off the coast of [[Africa]] on September 8 approached the area. A cold front merged with the stationary area of disturbed weather on September 20, and on September 22 a circulation developed 200&nbsp;miles (325&nbsp;km) southeast of [[Cape Hatteras]], [[North Carolina]].<ref name=\"nhcreportpg1\">{{cite web|author=Miles Lawrence|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report Page One|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/prenhc/prelim01.gif}}</ref> Organization continued as outflow became better defined, and the system developed into Tropical Depression Six later that day.<ref name=\"disc1\">{{cite web|author=Lixion Avila|year=1992|title=Tropical Depression Six Discussion One|publisher=NHC|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/tropdisc/nal0792.001}}</ref>\n\nThe depression rapidly organized and attained tropical storm status with winds of 50&nbsp;mph (80&nbsp;km/h) just six hours after forming, upon which it was named [[Danielle]]. In response to an approaching trough, Danielle initially moved to the northeast. However, the trough outran the system, and a developing high pressure system to its north resulted in Danielle executing a tight, anticyclonic loop on September 23 to the 24th. The storm strengthened as it turned to the northwest, and reached a peak of 65&nbsp;mph (105&nbsp;km/h) winds on September 25 while just off the northeastern coast of North Carolina. Danielle turned to the north-northwest, and made landfall on the [[Eastern Shore of Virginia|Eastern Shore]] of [[Virginia]] late on the 25th. It rapidly weakened over land, and dissipated over eastern [[Pennsylvania]] on September 26.<ref name=\"nhcreportpg1\"/>\n\n== Preparations ==\n[[File:Danielle radar.JPG|right|thumb|Radar image of Danielle making landfall on September 25]]\nEarly in its life, forecasters had difficulties regarding the future track and intensity of Danielle, including a northeastward motion instead of its loop. After Danielle executed its loop, forecasters consistently predicted a landfall along the northeastern [[North Carolina]] coastline.<ref name=\"nhcreportpg2\">{{Cite report|author=Miles B. Lawrence|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report|page=2|publisher=NHC|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/prenhc/prelim02.gif}}</ref> As a result, officials issued [[Tropical cyclone warnings and watches|Tropical Storm Warnings]] for the coast of North Carolina on September 24, 36&nbsp;hours before the storm passed to the east of the state. The continued northward motion caught forecasters off guard, and consequentially tropical storm warnings were not issued for the [[Delmarva Peninsula]] until just 12&nbsp;hours before the storm made landfall. In addition, forecasters issued tropical storm warnings from [[Delaware]] through [[Watch Hill, Rhode Island]], as a precaution.<ref name=\"nhcreportpg5\">{{cite web|author=Miles B. Lawrence|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report|page=5|publisher=NHC|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/prenhc/prelim05.gif}}</ref>\n\nIn [[North Carolina]], ferry operations between [[Ocracoke, North Carolina|Ocracoke]] and the mainland at [[Hyde County, North Carolina|Hyde County]] were closed, while officials canceled schools in [[Dare County, North Carolina]] due to the approaching storm.<ref name=\"kdcnews\">{{Cite web|author=Virginia Pilot|year=1992|title=Danielle destroys three beach cottages|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/news/vp0926p2.gif}}</ref> Several families voluntarily evacuated St. George's Island in southern [[St. Mary's County, Maryland]].<ref name=\"bwipr\">{{cite web|author=Davis|year=1992|title=Danielle Preliminary Report|publisher=Baltimore National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/pshbwi.gif}}</ref> In addition, officials in [[Delaware]] recommended evacuations for low-level areas and beaches. As a precaution, officials set up two shelters in [[Kent County, Delaware|Kent County]].<ref name=\"ilg5\">{{cite web|author=James N. Roets|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Summary for Delaware|publisher=Wilmington National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/ilg05.gif}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n\n=== North Carolina ===\nThe pressure gradient between Tropical Storm Danielle and a ridge of high pressure to its north produced moderately strong winds across eastern [[North Carolina]], peaking at 58&nbsp;mph (93&nbsp;km/h) at [[Alligator River National Wildlife Refuge|Alligator River Bridge]]. Several other locations reported over tropical storm force winds. The pressure gradient also produced higher than normal waves along the coastline, with a maximum of 20&nbsp;feet (6&nbsp;m) at [[Duck, North Carolina|Duck]].<ref name=\"rdu03\">{{cite web|author=Glenn A. Field|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Report|publisher=Raleigh National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-05|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/rdu03.gif}}</ref> Despite passing close to the coastline, Danielle dropped only light rainfall, totaling to 0.2&nbsp;inches (5&nbsp;mm) at [[Cape Hatteras, North Carolina|Cape Hatteras]].<ref name=\"hatpsh\">{{cite web|author=Demaurice|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report|publisher=Cape Hatteras National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-05|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/pshhat.gif}}</ref> However, locations in the central portion of the state experienced over 1&nbsp;inch (25&nbsp;mm) of rainfall.<ref name=\"rain\">{{cite web|author=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|year=2005|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Rainfall Summary|accessdate=2006-08-05|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/danielle1992.html}}</ref>\n\nWaves and high tides from the storm caused flooding along the [[Pamlico Sound]] side of [[Ocracoke, North Carolina|Ocracoke]] and southern [[Hatteras Island]]. High tides also resulted in overwash in [[Pea Island]], forcing the closure of [[North Carolina Highway 12|Highway 12]] due to 12&nbsp;inches (305&nbsp;mm) of salt water. High tides from the storm also destroyed two houses in [[South Nags Head, North Carolina|South Nags Head]] and one in [[Rodanthe, North Carolina|Rodanthe]], two of which were previously condemned after the [[1991 Perfect Storm]]. Three other houses in the Outer Banks were threatened by the storm.<ref name=\"hatpsh\"/> Elsewhere in the Outer Banks, damage was minimal, and was limited to pedestrian ramps and steps to the beachfront.<ref name=\"kdcnews\"/>\n\n=== Mid-Atlantic ===\n\nIn [[Virginia]], Tropical Storm Danielle produced peak wind gusts of 61&nbsp;mph (98&nbsp;km/h) at [[Cape Henry]], though sustained winds remained below tropical storm strength. Rainfall was light along the coast, totaling to around 0.34&nbsp;inches (8.6&nbsp;mm).<ref name=\"norfnws\">{{cite web|author=Norfolk National Weather Service|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Preliminary Report|accessdate=2006-08-06|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/pshorf.gif}}</ref> However, outer bands of the storm produced heavier rainfall in the center portion of the state, peaking at 4.09&nbsp;inches (103.88&nbsp;m) at [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]].<ref name=\"metsum\">{{cite report|author=Miles B. Lawrence|year=1992|title=Meteorological Statistics for Danielle|publisher=NHC|accessdate=2006-08-06|page=4|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/prenhc/prelim04.gif}}</ref> The storm also produced higher than usual tides, peaking at 4.42&nbsp;feet (1.3&nbsp;m) at the mouth of the [[Elizabeth River (Virginia)|Elizabeth River]] in [[Sewell's Point|Sewells Point]],<ref name=\"norfnws\"/> as well as strong waves along the Virginia coastline. The waves caused significant overwash, leaving parts of [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]] under 2&nbsp;feet (.6&nbsp;m) of water. Several homes, businesses, and cars were flooded, as well. The waves also eroded beaches along the coast.<ref name=\"vapilot\">{{cite web|author=Steve Stone|year=1992|title=Coast is spared the worst of unpredictable Danielle|publisher=Virginia Pilot|accessdate=2006-08-06|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/news/vp0926p1.gif}}</ref> Overall, damage was minimal, and there were no reports of deaths or injuries.<ref name=\"norfnws\"/>\n\nUpon making landfall Danielle produced an estimated storm tide of 2 to 3&nbsp;feet (.6 to .9&nbsp;m) in [[Ocean City, Maryland|Ocean City]], [[Maryland]]. Wind gusts peaked at 53&nbsp;mph (85&nbsp;km/h), also in Ocean City.<ref name=\"bwipr\"/> The storm produced moderate rainfall of over 3&nbsp;inches (76&nbsp;mm) across the [[Eastern Shore of Maryland]],<ref name=\"rain\"/> while interior amounts experienced slightly lesser amounts of up to 2.79&nbsp;inches (71&nbsp;mm) in [[Pasadena, Maryland|Pasadena]]. Waves from the storm caused minor to moderate beach erosion along the coastline, and the combination of waves and high tides caused moderate street flooding. Near [[Salisbury, Maryland|Salisbury]], the storm produced a possible hook echo, though no tornadoes were reported. Danielle caused no deaths or injuries in the state.<ref name=\"bwipr\"/>\n\nIn [[Delaware]], the storm dropped light precipitation, with a maximum amount of 3.75&nbsp;inches (95&nbsp;mm) in [[Smyrna, Delaware|Smyrna]]. Wind gusts peaked at 66&nbsp;mph (106&nbsp;km/h) at [[Cape Henlopen]].<ref name=\"metsum\"/> Danielle caused 2 to 3-foot (.6 to .9-m) higher than normal tides, along with strong waves. The combination of the two flooded some coastal houses<ref name=\"ilg5\"/> and resulted in significant beach and dune erosion. The waves also sank four boats and washed away a dock near [[Slaughter Beach, Delaware|Slaughter Beach]].<ref name=\"ilg1\">{{cite web|author=James N. Roets|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Summary for Delaware|publisher=Wilmington National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-08|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/ilg01.gif}}</ref> Gusty winds caused power outages in [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]], while persistent rainfall caused sewer interruptions. Overall, with the exception of the severe beach erosion, damage was minimal.<ref name=\"ilg6\">{{cite web|author=James N. Roets|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm Danielle Summary for Delaware|publisher=Wilmington National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-08|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/preloc/ilg06.gif}}</ref>\n\n=== Northeast United States ===\nTropical Storm Danielle dropped light rainfall across much of [[New Jersey]], with some areas in the southwestern portion of the state experiencing over 3&nbsp;inches (76&nbsp;mm).<ref name=\"rain\"/> Strong waves from the storm washed out miles of beaches along the coastline. In [[Ocean City, New Jersey|Ocean City]], the waves passed over the boardwalk and into houses. Further north, the waves crashed a four-person, 35-foot (10-m) sailboat near [[Island Beach State Park]]. Two managed to swim safely to shore,<ref name=\"mhdan\">{{cite web|author=Associated Press|year=1992|title=Tropical Storm blamed on one death|accessdate=2006-08-09|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1992/danielle/news/mh0927p1.gif}}</ref> though the other two occupants drowned.<ref name=\"nccanes\">{{Cite web|author=James E. Hudgins|year=2000|title=Tropical cyclones affecting North Carolina since 1586|publisher=National Weather Service|accessdate=2006-08-09|url=http://repository.wrclib.noaa.gov/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1002&context=nws_tech_memos|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070311045226/http://repository.wrclib.noaa.gov/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1002&context=nws_tech_memos |archivedate = March 11, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDanielle's outer bands dropped light rainfall from [[Connecticut]] through [[Maine]], with isolated locations in [[Rhode Island]] and [[Massachusetts]] reporting over 3&nbsp;inches (76&nbsp;mm). Damage in New England is unknown.<ref name=\"rain\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n* [[Hurricane Danielle (disambiguation)|Other storms of the same name]]\n* [[List of North Carolina hurricanes]]\n* [[List of New Jersey hurricanes]]\n* [[Timeline of the 1992 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Tropcial Storm Danielle (1992)}}\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{1992 Atlantic hurricane season buttons}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Danielle (1992)}}\n[[Category:1992 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Atlantic tropical storms]]\n[[Category:1992 natural disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:sp Tropcial > Tropical - The typo at commons has been fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tropical_Storm_Danielle_(1992)"}
{"title_page": "Biggie & Tupac", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Biggie & Tupac\n| image          = Biggie & Tupac DVD.jpg\n| caption        = DVD Cover for Biggie & Tupac\n| producer       = [[Nick Broomfield]]<br />[[Michele D'Acosta]]\n| director       = [[Nick Broomfield]]\n| writer         =\n| starring       = [[Biggie Smalls]] (archive footage)<br />[[Tupac Shakur]] (archive footage)<br />[[Nick Broomfield]]<br />[[Russell Poole]]<br />Voletta Wallace<br />[[Billy Garland (Ex Black Panther)|Billy Garland]]<br />[[David Hicken]]<br />[[Suge Knight]]\n| music          = [[Christian Henson]]\n| cinematography = [[Joan Churchill]]\n| editing        = Mark Atkins<br />[[Jaime Estrada Torres]]\n| distributor    = [[Roxie Theater|Roxie Releasing]]<br />[[Lions Gate Entertainment]]\n| released       = January 11, 2002\n| runtime        = 108 min.\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Biggie & Tupac''''' is a 2002 feature-length [[documentary film]] about murdered rappers [[The Notorious B.I.G.|Christopher \"Notorious B.I.G.\" Wallace]] and [[Tupac Shakur|Tupac \"2Pac\" Shakur]] by [[Nick Broomfield]].\n\nBroomfield suggests the two murders were planned by [[Suge Knight]], head of [[Death Row Records]]. Collusion by the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] (LAPD) is also implied.<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20030110/REVIEWS/301100302/1023 Biggie & Tupac], rogerebert.com</ref> While the film remains inconclusive, when asked \"Who killed Tupac?\" in a [[BBC]] Radio interview dated March 7, 2005, Broomfield stated (quoting [[Snoop Dogg]]) \"The big guy next to him in the car... Suge Knight.\" Often accompanied by Alannah Haugh on triangle.\n\n== Content ==\n\nThe film alleges that Knight had Tupac killed before he could part ways with Knight's Death Row label and conspired to kill Biggie to divert attention from himself in the Tupac murder.<ref name=\"Broomfield's Biggie and Tupac reviewed by the Courant\">{{cite news|last=Danton|first=Eric|title=Biggie (rip) Vs. Tupac (rip)|url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-11-09/features/0211090122_1_tupac-shakur-jam-master-jay-death-row-records|accessdate=8 November 2013|newspaper=The Courant|date=November 9, 2003}}</ref> Broomfield's documentary is based on the theory and interviews of ex-detective Russell Poole. Poole claimed that the L.A.P.D. conspired to cover up Suge Knight's conspiracy to kill Tupac and Biggie. Ex-detective Russell Poole suspected ex-cop David Mack, and Amir Muhammed to have worked with Suge Knight to kill Biggie. Poole also alleged that he was forced out of the department when he brought information to his superiors incriminating fellow officers who had worked side jobs as bodyguards for Knight and his record label.\n\nA key source for Poole's theory is Kevin Hackie. Hackie implicates Suge Knight and David Mack along with supposed crooked cops in the murder of Biggie. When pressed by Broomfield in the film, Hackie agrees that Harry Billups, also known as Amir Muhammed, was involved in the murder, although Hackie says he does not know why.  Hackie, a former Death Row bodyguard, wrote in a statement filed June 6, 2004 that he had \"\"personal knowledge\" about Wallace's slaying, alleging that \"persons within Death Row Records offered $25,000 to a law enforcement officer\" to kill Wallace.<ref name=\"Lawsuit witness admits to false declaration\">{{cite news|last=Philips|first=Chuck|title=Witness in B.I.G. case says his memory's bad|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-biggie20jun20,0,1053108.story|accessdate=3 October 2013|newspaper=LA Times|date=June 20, 2005}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nBroomfield's documentary is described by the ''New York Times''<ref name=\"Leland\">{{cite news|last=Leland|first=John|title=New Theories Stir Speculation On Rap Deaths|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/07/arts/new-theories-stir-speculation-on-rap-deaths.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=30 September 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=October 7, 2002}}</ref> as a \"largely speculative\" and \"circumstantial\"<ref name=\"Leland\" /> account relying on flimsy evidence, failing to \"present counter-evidence\" or \"question sources.\"  As ''The Courant'' noted: <blockquote>Broomfield's interview subjects aren't the most credible bunch. They include bounty hunter and ex-con Kevin Hackie, an ex-LAPD officer [Russell Poole on whose theory Broomfield's film is built] who talks about mysterious documents that never turn up; Mark Hyland, known for some reason as the Bookkeeper, who is in prison awaiting trial on 37 counts of impersonating a lawyer when he tells Broomfield that he was present when Knight and crooked cops arranged a hit on Biggie; and Biggie's mother, friends and bodyguard, who obviously have no reason to present Wallace as anything less than a hip-hop martyr.<ref name=\"Broomfield's Biggie and Tupac reviewed by the Courant\">{{cite news|last=Danton|first=Eric|title=Biggie (rip) Vs. Tupac (rip)|url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-11-09/features/0211090122_1_tupac-shakur-jam-master-jay-death-row-records|accessdate=8 November 2013|newspaper=The Courant|date=November 9, 2003}}</ref> </blockquote> Moreover, the motive suggested for the murder of Biggie (as in the Russell Poole theory on which it relied) -- to decrease suspicion for the Shakur shooting six months earlier\u2014was, as ''The New York Times'' phrased it, \"unsupported in the film.\"<ref name=\"Leland\" />\n\n== Later events ==\n\nIn an interview, Hackie later told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' that he suffered memory lapses due to psychiatric medications.<ref name=\"Lawsuit witness admits to false declaration\">{{cite news|last=Philips|first=Chuck|title=Witness in B.I.G. case says his memory's bad|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-biggie20jun20,0,1053108.story|accessdate=3 October 2013|newspaper=LA Times|date=June 20, 2005}}</ref>  The Wallace family used his claims in the film as the basis of their $500 million lawsuit against the city of L.A. for Biggie's death. But Hackie later told the ''LA Times'' that the Wallace attorneys had altered his statements and he did not testify in their suit.<ref name=\"Lawsuit witness admits to false declaration\">{{cite news|last=Philips|first=Chuck|title=Witness in B.I.G. case says his memory's bad|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-biggie20jun20,0,1053108.story|accessdate=3 October 2013|newspaper=LA Times|date=June 20, 2005}}</ref> (The 500 million dollar suit was dismissed in 2010.)\n\nA 2005 article in the ''LA Times'', saying that another source for the Poole/Sullivan theory accusing Amir Muhammed, David Mack, Suge Knight and the L.A.P.D. in the Wallace suit was a schizophrenic known as \"Psycho Mike\" who confessed to hearsay and memory lapses and falsely identifying Amir Muhammed.<ref name=\"Chuck Philips on Biggie murder\">{{cite news|last=Philips|first=Chuck|title=Informant in Rap Star's Slaying Admits Hearsay|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/jun/03/local/me-biggie3|accessdate=15 September 2013|newspaper=LA Times|date=June 3, 2005}}</ref> John Cook of [[Brill's Content]] noted that the ''LA Times'' article \"demolished\" <ref name=\"Notorious LAT; by original Brill's content author of eponymous article John Cook\">{{cite web|last=Cook|first=John|title=Notorious LAT|url=http://www.referencetone.com/2005/06/notorious-lat.html|publisher=Reference tone|date=June 2005|access-date=2013-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002123203/http://www.referencetone.com/2005/06/notorious-lat.html|archive-date=2013-10-02|url-status=dead}}</ref> the Poole-Sullvan theory of Biggie's murder represented in the film.\n\nIn contrast to Broomfield's implication of Suge Knight in the death of Tupac, a 2002 two-part series by reporter [[Chuck Philips]] with the ''Times'', titled \u201cWho Killed Tupac Shakur?\u201d based on a year-long investigation, reconstructing the events leading up to Shakur's murder including police affidavits, court documents and interviews with investigators, supposed witnesses to the crime and members of the Southside Crips <ref name=\"Philips: Who killed Tupac Shakur\">{{cite news|last=Philips|first=Chuck|title=Who Killed Tupac Shakur?|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/06/business/fi-tupac6|accessdate=15 July 2012|newspaper=LA Times|date=6 September 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Police probe in [[Tupac Shakur]]\">{{cite news|last=Philips|first=Chuck|title=How Vegas police probe floundered in Tupac Shakur case|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-fi-tupac7sep07,0,6002100.story|accessdate=23 July 2012|newspaper=LA Times|date=September 7, 2002}}</ref> claimed that \u201cthe shooting was carried out by a Compton gang called the Southside Crips to avenge the beating of one of its members by Shakur a few hours earlier. [[Orlando Anderson]], the Crip whom Shakur had attacked, fired the fatal shots. Las Vegas police discounted Anderson as a suspect and interviewed him only once, briefly. He was later killed in an unrelated gang shooting.\u201d<ref name=\"Philips: Who killed Tupac Shakur\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Notorious (2009 film)]]\n*[[All Eyez on Me (film)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|0303356}}\n*[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/l-a-times-responds-to-biggie-story-20060112 Letter to the editor, ''Rolling Stone'' magazine]\n\n{{Nick Broomfield}}\n{{2Pac}}\n{{The Notorious B.I.G.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biggie and Tupac}}\n[[Category:2000s documentary films]]\n[[Category:2002 films]]\n[[Category:British documentary films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about African-American gangs]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about hip hop music and musicians]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Nick Broomfield]]\n[[Category:Works about Tupac Shakur]]\n[[Category:The Notorious B.I.G.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Biggie & Tupac\n| image          = Biggie & Tupac DVD.jpg\n| caption        = DVD Cover for Biggie & Tupac\n| producer       = [[Nick Broomfield]]<br />[[Michele D'Acosta]]\n| director       = [[Nick Broomfield]]\n| writer         =\n| starring       = [[Biggie Smalls]] (archive footage)<br />[[Tupac Shakur]] (archive footage)<br />[[Nick Broomfield]]<br />[[Russell Poole]]<br />Voletta Wallace<br />[[Billy Garland (Ex Black Panther)|Billy Garland]]<br />[[David Hicken]]<br />[[Suge Knight]]\n| music          = [[Christian Henson]]\n| cinematography = [[Joan Churchill]]\n| editing        = Mark Atkins<br />[[Jaime Estrada Torres]]\n| distributor    = [[Roxie Theater|Roxie Releasing]]<br />[[Lions Gate Entertainment]]\n| released       = January 11, 2002\n| runtime        = 108 min.\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Biggie & Tupac''''' is a 2002 feature-length [[documentary film]] about murdered rappers [[The Notorious B.I.G.|Christopher \"Notorious B.I.G.\" Wallace]] and [[Tupac Shakur|Tupac \"2Pac\" Shakur]] by [[Nick Broomfield]].\n\nBroomfield suggests the two murders were planned by [[Suge Knight]], head of [[Death Row Records]]. Collusion by the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] (LAPD) is also implied.<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20030110/REVIEWS/301100302/1023 Biggie & Tupac], rogerebert.com</ref> While the film remains inconclusive, when asked \"Who killed Tupac?\" in a [[BBC]] Radio interview dated March 7, 2005, Broomfield stated (quoting [[Snoop Dogg]]) \"The big guy next to him in the car... Suge Knight.\"\n\n== Content ==\n\nThe film alleges that Knight had Tupac killed before he could part ways with Knight's Death Row label and conspired to kill Biggie to divert attention from himself in the Tupac murder.<ref name=\"Broomfield's Biggie and Tupac reviewed by the Courant\">{{cite news|last=Danton|first=Eric|title=Biggie (rip) Vs. Tupac (rip)|url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-11-09/features/0211090122_1_tupac-shakur-jam-master-jay-death-row-records|accessdate=8 November 2013|newspaper=The Courant|date=November 9, 2003}}</ref> Broomfield's documentary is based on the theory and interviews of ex-detective Russell Poole. Poole claimed that the L.A.P.D. conspired to cover up Suge Knight's conspiracy to kill Tupac and Biggie. Ex-detective Russell Poole suspected ex-cop David Mack, and Amir Muhammed to have worked with Suge Knight to kill Biggie. Poole also alleged that he was forced out of the department when he brought information to his superiors incriminating fellow officers who had worked side jobs as bodyguards for Knight and his record label.\n\nA key source for Poole's theory is Kevin Hackie. Hackie implicates Suge Knight and David Mack along with supposed crooked cops in the murder of Biggie. When pressed by Broomfield in the film, Hackie agrees that Harry Billups, also known as Amir Muhammed, was involved in the murder, although Hackie says he does not know why.  Hackie, a former Death Row bodyguard, wrote in a statement filed June 6, 2004 that he had \"\"personal knowledge\" about Wallace's slaying, alleging that \"persons within Death Row Records offered $25,000 to a law enforcement officer\" to kill Wallace.<ref name=\"Lawsuit witness admits to false declaration\">{{cite news|last=Philips|first=Chuck|title=Witness in B.I.G. case says his memory's bad|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-biggie20jun20,0,1053108.story|accessdate=3 October 2013|newspaper=LA Times|date=June 20, 2005}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nBroomfield's documentary is described by the ''New York Times''<ref name=\"Leland\">{{cite news|last=Leland|first=John|title=New Theories Stir Speculation On Rap Deaths|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/07/arts/new-theories-stir-speculation-on-rap-deaths.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=30 September 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=October 7, 2002}}</ref> as a \"largely speculative\" and \"circumstantial\"<ref name=\"Leland\" /> acco